with b as (
  insert into tests (title, topic, difficulty, duration_minutes)
  values ($x$w3-basic-c — ingested draft, verify before trusting$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, 'medium', 60)
  returning id
)
insert into questions (test_id, position, question, options, correct_index, explanation, topic, difficulty)
select b.id, v.pos::int, v.question, v.options::jsonb, v.ci::int, v.exp, v.topic, v.diff
from b, (values
  (0, $x$Which nephron segment reabsorbs the largest fraction of the filtered sodium and water?$x$, $x$["Collecting duct","Proximal convoluted tubule","Distal convoluted tubule","Thick ascending limb of Henle"]$x$, 1, $x$The proximal convoluted tubule reabsorbs about 65% of the filtered sodium and water isosmotically. Reabsorption here is driven by basolateral Na+-K+ ATPase and is largely obligatory.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (1, $x$Which substance is the gold standard for measuring GFR because it is freely filtered but neither reabsorbed nor secreted?$x$, $x$["Glucose","Inulin","Para-aminohippuric acid","Sodium"]$x$, 1, $x$Inulin is freely filtered and neither reabsorbed nor secreted, so its clearance equals the GFR. Creatinine clearance approximates GFR clinically but is slightly higher due to some tubular secretion.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (2, $x$The active transport that drives the counter-current multiplier and generates medullary hyperosmolarity occurs in the:$x$, $x$["Thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle","Cortical collecting duct","Proximal convoluted tubule","Thin descending limb"]$x$, 0, $x$The thick ascending limb actively pumps NaCl out via the Na-K-2Cl cotransporter while remaining impermeable to water. This creates the single effect that the counter-current arrangement multiplies into a steep medullary osmotic gradient.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (3, $x$The clearance of which substance is used to estimate the effective renal plasma flow?$x$, $x$["Urea","Inulin","Para-aminohippuric acid","Creatinine"]$x$, 2, $x$PAH is almost completely filtered and secreted, so nearly all of it is cleared in a single pass through the kidney. Its clearance therefore estimates the effective renal plasma flow.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (4, $x$Mild constriction of the efferent arteriole alone will:$x$, $x$["Decrease the glomerular filtration rate","Abolish filtration completely","Increase the glomerular filtration rate","Leave GFR unchanged"]$x$, 2, $x$Efferent constriction raises the glomerular capillary hydrostatic pressure upstream, which increases the net filtration pressure and GFR. Severe or prolonged constriction eventually lowers renal plasma flow and can reduce GFR.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (5, $x$Contraction of the detrusor muscle during micturition is mediated mainly by:$x$, $x$["Sympathetic fibres in the hypogastric nerve","Somatic fibres in the pudendal nerve","Parasympathetic fibres in the pelvic nerve (S2-S4)","The vagus nerve"]$x$, 2, $x$The micturition reflex is a parasympathetic spinal reflex carried by the pelvic nerves from S2-S4. These fibres cause detrusor contraction while the internal sphincter relaxes to allow voiding.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (6, $x$The principal muscle responsible for quiet inspiration is the:$x$, $x$["Diaphragm","Internal intercostal muscle","Abdominal muscles","Sternocleidomastoid"]$x$, 0, $x$The diaphragm performs about 70% of the work of quiet inspiration by descending and enlarging the thoracic cavity. Accessory muscles like the sternocleidomastoid are recruited only during forced breathing.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (7, $x$Lung compliance is best defined as:$x$, $x$["The pressure needed to overcome airway resistance","The change in pressure per unit change in volume","The change in lung volume per unit change in transpulmonary pressure","The product of volume and pressure"]$x$, 2, $x$Compliance is the change in lung volume per unit change in distending (transpulmonary) pressure, reflecting the distensibility of the lungs. It is reduced in fibrosis and increased in emphysema.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (8, $x$In an upright person, the ventilation-perfusion (V/Q) ratio at the apex of the lung is:$x$, $x$["Less than 1","Greater than 1","Exactly zero","Equal to 1"]$x$, 1, $x$At the apex, blood flow falls more than ventilation because of gravity, so the V/Q ratio is high (about 3). At the base the ratio is low (about 0.6) because perfusion exceeds ventilation.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (9, $x$All of the following shift the oxygen-haemoglobin dissociation curve to the RIGHT EXCEPT:$x$, $x$["Increased temperature","Increased 2,3-bisphosphoglycerate","Increased blood pH (alkalosis)","Increased PCO2"]$x$, 2, $x$A rightward shift indicates reduced haemoglobin affinity and is caused by increased H+, CO2, temperature and 2,3-BPG. A rise in pH (alkalosis) is a Bohr effect that shifts the curve to the left, raising affinity.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (10, $x$The central chemoreceptors in the medulla are stimulated most directly by:$x$, $x$["A fall in arterial PO2","A rise in H+ concentration of brain ECF produced by CO2","A fall in H+ concentration of the CSF","A rise in arterial PO2"]$x$, 1, $x$CO2 diffuses across the blood-brain barrier and generates H+ in the CSF and brain extracellular fluid, which stimulates the central chemoreceptors. They do not respond to low PO2, which is sensed by the peripheral chemoreceptors.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (11, $x$The intrinsic coagulation pathway is assessed clinically by the:$x$, $x$["Reticulocyte count","Prothrombin time (PT)","Activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT)","Bleeding time"]$x$, 2, $x$The aPTT tests the intrinsic and common pathways, while the prothrombin time tests the extrinsic and common pathways. The bleeding time reflects platelet and vascular function rather than the coagulation cascade.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (12, $x$The extrinsic coagulation pathway is triggered by:$x$, $x$["Activation of factor XII on a foreign surface","Platelet factor 4","Von Willebrand factor","Release of tissue factor (factor III)"]$x$, 3, $x$The extrinsic pathway begins when tissue factor released from damaged tissue activates factor VII. The intrinsic pathway instead starts with contact activation of factor XII on a negatively charged surface.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (13, $x$During fibrinolysis, plasminogen is converted to active plasmin mainly by:$x$, $x$["Antithrombin III","Thrombin","Tissue plasminogen activator (tPA)","Factor XIII"]$x$, 2, $x$Tissue plasminogen activator converts plasminogen to plasmin, which digests fibrin and dissolves the clot. Factor XIII in contrast cross-links fibrin to stabilise the clot rather than break it down.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (14, $x$Platelet aggregation at the site of injury is promoted by the release of:$x$, $x$["Heparin","Nitric oxide","Thromboxane A2","Prostacyclin (PGI2)"]$x$, 2, $x$Thromboxane A2 produced by activated platelets promotes aggregation and vasoconstriction. Prostacyclin and nitric oxide from healthy endothelium oppose this by inhibiting aggregation.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (15, $x$A person with blood group AB has which antibodies in the plasma?$x$, $x$["Anti-A only","Both anti-A and anti-B","Neither anti-A nor anti-B","Anti-B only"]$x$, 2, $x$Group AB red cells carry both A and B antigens, so the plasma contains neither anti-A nor anti-B antibodies. This makes AB individuals universal recipients for red cell transfusion.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (16, $x$Haemolytic disease of the newborn due to Rh incompatibility typically occurs when:$x$, $x$["The mother is Rh negative and the fetus Rh positive","The mother is Rh positive and the fetus Rh negative","Both mother and fetus are Rh negative","Both mother and fetus are Rh positive"]$x$, 0, $x$An Rh-negative mother carrying an Rh-positive fetus can become sensitised and produce anti-D IgG antibodies. In a subsequent Rh-positive pregnancy these cross the placenta and cause fetal haemolysis.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (17, $x$The erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) is typically increased by:$x$, $x$["Sickle-shaped red cells","A rise in plasma fibrinogen and globulins","Very low plasma protein levels","Polycythaemia"]$x$, 1, $x$High plasma fibrinogen and globulins promote rouleaux formation, so red cells settle faster and the ESR rises. Polycythaemia and abnormally shaped cells such as sickle cells hinder rouleaux and lower the ESR.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (18, $x$The most important buffer of the extracellular fluid is the:$x$, $x$["Intracellular protein buffer","Bicarbonate-carbonic acid buffer system","Ammonia buffer system","Phosphate buffer system"]$x$, 1, $x$The bicarbonate-carbonic acid system is the principal extracellular buffer because both components are independently regulated by the lungs and kidneys. This open system gives it far greater effective buffering power than its pK alone would suggest.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (19, $x$The respiratory compensation for a primary metabolic acidosis is:$x$, $x$["Hyperventilation that lowers arterial PCO2","Increased renal bicarbonate excretion","Hypoventilation that raises arterial PCO2","No respiratory change"]$x$, 0, $x$The excess H+ stimulates peripheral chemoreceptors, causing hyperventilation that blows off CO2 and lowers arterial PCO2. This Kussmaul breathing partially restores the pH toward normal.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (20, $x$Which condition characteristically produces a HIGH anion-gap metabolic acidosis?$x$, $x$["Prolonged diarrhoea","Excess normal saline infusion","Diabetic ketoacidosis","Type 1 (distal) renal tubular acidosis"]$x$, 2, $x$In diabetic ketoacidosis, unmeasured keto-acid anions accumulate and widen the anion gap. Diarrhoea and renal tubular acidosis instead cause a normal anion-gap acidosis due to bicarbonate loss with chloride retention.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (21, $x$The resting membrane potential of a typical neurone (about -70 mV) is maintained mainly by:$x$, $x$["High resting permeability to chloride only","High resting permeability to potassium plus the Na+-K+ pump","High resting permeability to sodium","High resting permeability to calcium"]$x$, 1, $x$At rest the membrane is far more permeable to potassium than to sodium, so the potential lies close to the potassium equilibrium potential. The Na+-K+ ATPase maintains the ionic gradients and adds a small electrogenic contribution.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (22, $x$The rapid depolarization (upstroke) phase of the nerve action potential is due to:$x$, $x$["Influx of sodium ions","Efflux of potassium ions","Efflux of calcium ions","Influx of chloride ions"]$x$, 0, $x$The upstroke results from rapid opening of voltage-gated sodium channels and a large sodium influx down its electrochemical gradient. This drives the membrane potential toward the sodium equilibrium potential.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (23, $x$Repolarization of the neuronal action potential is produced mainly by:$x$, $x$["Influx of chloride ions","Continued sodium influx","Efflux of potassium ions through voltage-gated K+ channels","The sodium-potassium pump acting instantaneously"]$x$, 2, $x$Repolarization occurs as sodium channels inactivate and voltage-gated potassium channels open, allowing potassium to leave the cell. This restores the negative interior and often causes a brief after-hyperpolarization.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (24, $x$At a chemical synapse, the immediate trigger for neurotransmitter release from the presynaptic terminal is:$x$, $x$["Influx of chloride","Influx of calcium into the presynaptic terminal","Efflux of potassium from the terminal","Efflux of sodium"]$x$, 1, $x$Depolarization opens voltage-gated calcium channels, and the calcium influx triggers fusion of synaptic vesicles with the presynaptic membrane. Neurotransmitter is then released into the cleft by exocytosis.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (25, $x$During the absolute refractory period of a nerve fibre:$x$, $x$["A stronger-than-normal stimulus can produce an action potential","The sodium channels are fully available for activation","No stimulus, however strong, can generate another action potential","The membrane is hyperpolarized by potassium efflux only"]$x$, 2, $x$In the absolute refractory period the sodium channels are inactivated, so no stimulus of any strength can trigger a new action potential. This period sets the maximum firing frequency and ensures one-way propagation.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (26, $x$The principal integrating centre for the regulation of body temperature is the:$x$, $x$["Medulla oblongata","Cerebellum","Hypothalamus","Thalamus"]$x$, 2, $x$The hypothalamus acts as the body's thermostat, comparing core temperature with a set point. It coordinates heat-loss and heat-conserving responses through autonomic, endocrine and behavioural pathways.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (27, $x$The only mechanism by which the body can lose heat when the environmental temperature exceeds body temperature is:$x$, $x$["Evaporation of sweat","Conduction","Radiation","Convection"]$x$, 0, $x$When the surroundings are hotter than the body, radiation, conduction and convection add heat rather than remove it. Evaporation of sweat is then the sole avenue for losing heat and requires low humidity to work.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (28, $x$Stimulation of the anterior hypothalamic-preoptic area causes:$x$, $x$["Increased thyroid hormone secretion only","Piloerection to conserve heat","Sweating and cutaneous vasodilatation (heat loss)","Shivering and cutaneous vasoconstriction"]$x$, 2, $x$The anterior hypothalamic-preoptic area drives heat-loss responses such as sweating and cutaneous vasodilatation. The posterior hypothalamus instead mediates heat conservation and production through vasoconstriction and shivering.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$hard$x$)
) as v(pos, question, options, ci, exp, topic, diff);

-- 28-community-biostat.txt — 30 questions
with b as (
  insert into tests (title, topic, difficulty, duration_minutes)
  values ($x$w3-community-d — ingested draft, verify before trusting$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, 'medium', 60)
  returning id
)
insert into questions (test_id, position, question, options, correct_index, explanation, topic, difficulty)
select b.id, v.pos::int, v.question, v.options::jsonb, v.ci::int, v.exp, v.topic, v.diff
from b, (values
  (0, $x$The chi-square test is most appropriate for analysing which type of data?$x$, $x$["Paired continuous measurements from the same individuals","Qualitative (categorical) data expressed as frequencies","Ranked ordinal data from a single small sample","Continuous quantitative data that is normally distributed"]$x$, 1, $x$The chi-square test assesses the association between qualitative or categorical variables using observed and expected frequencies in a contingency table. It is a non-parametric test of significance for enumeration data.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (1, $x$The value of the correlation coefficient (r) always lies between which of the following limits?$x$, $x$["0 and +100","-100 and +100","-1 and +1","0 and +1"]$x$, 2, $x$Karl Pearson's correlation coefficient ranges from -1 (perfect negative correlation) through 0 (no correlation) to +1 (perfect positive correlation). Its sign shows the direction and its magnitude shows the strength of the linear relationship.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (2, $x$The standard error of the mean is calculated as:$x$, $x$["Variance divided by the sample size","Square root of the standard deviation","Standard deviation multiplied by the sample size","Standard deviation divided by the square root of the sample size"]$x$, 3, $x$The standard error of the mean equals the standard deviation divided by the square root of the sample size (SD/√n). It measures the precision of the sample mean as an estimate of the population mean and falls as sample size increases.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (3, $x$Student's t-test is the test of choice for comparing:$x$, $x$["Association between two categorical variables","Means of two small samples (n less than 30)","More than two group means simultaneously","Proportions in two large samples"]$x$, 1, $x$The t-test compares the means of small samples (n less than 30) when the population standard deviation is unknown and the data are approximately normally distributed. For comparing more than two means, analysis of variance (ANOVA) is used.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (4, $x$A type I error in hypothesis testing occurs when the investigator:$x$, $x$["Increases the sample size unnecessarily","Uses a two-tailed instead of a one-tailed test","Accepts a null hypothesis that is actually false","Rejects a null hypothesis that is actually true"]$x$, 3, $x$A type I (alpha) error is the rejection of a true null hypothesis, meaning a difference is concluded when none really exists. Its probability equals the chosen level of significance, conventionally set at 0.05.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (5, $x$The probability of committing a type II error is denoted by:$x$, $x$["The power of the study","The confidence level","Beta","Alpha"]$x$, 2, $x$A type II error (beta) is the failure to reject a false null hypothesis, that is, missing a real difference. The power of a study equals 1 minus beta and reflects its ability to detect a true effect.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (6, $x$In tests of significance, a p-value less than 0.05 conventionally indicates that:$x$, $x$["The result is statistically significant","The sample size was too small","The null hypothesis is definitely true","The result is certainly due to chance"]$x$, 0, $x$A p-value below 0.05 means the observed result would arise by chance less than 5% of the time if the null hypothesis were true. It is therefore judged statistically significant and the null hypothesis is rejected.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (7, $x$A 95% confidence interval for a population mean is best interpreted as:$x$, $x$["There is a 95% chance the sample mean is exactly correct","The interval contains 95% of the raw sample values","95% of individual observations fall within the interval","The range within which the true population value lies with 95% confidence"]$x$, 3, $x$A 95% confidence interval is the range, computed from sample data, that would contain the true population parameter in 95% of repeated samples. It expresses the precision of the estimate, not the spread of individual observations.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (8, $x$For a contingency table with r rows and c columns, the degrees of freedom for the chi-square test are:$x$, $x$["r multiplied by c","(r-1)(c-1)","(r+c) minus 1","n minus 1"]$x$, 1, $x$The degrees of freedom for a chi-square test on an r by c contingency table equal (rows minus 1) multiplied by (columns minus 1). For a standard 2 by 2 table this gives one degree of freedom.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (9, $x$The primary purpose of regression analysis, as distinct from correlation, is to:$x$, $x$["Compare the variances of two samples","Test the significance of a single proportion","Predict the value of one variable from another","Measure only the strength of an association"]$x$, 2, $x$Regression estimates the average change in a dependent variable per unit change in an independent variable, allowing prediction of one from the other. Correlation only quantifies the strength and direction of the linear relationship.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (10, $x$A paired t-test would be the correct choice to analyse:$x$, $x$["Mean haemoglobin across four independent groups","The proportion of smokers in two different villages","Blood pressure before and after treatment in the same patients","Blood pressure of men versus women in a survey"]$x$, 2, $x$The paired t-test compares two measurements taken on the same individuals, such as before and after an intervention, thereby removing between-subject variation. Comparisons between independent groups require the unpaired t-test instead.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (11, $x$Which change would increase the power of a study to detect a true difference?$x$, $x$["Reducing the true effect size","Decreasing the sample size","Increasing the beta error","Increasing the sample size"]$x$, 3, $x$Statistical power (1 minus beta) rises with a larger sample size, a larger true effect size, and a higher significance level. A bigger sample reduces the standard error, making a genuine difference easier to detect.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (12, $x$A cohort study directly allows calculation of which measure of disease frequency?$x$, $x$["Odds ratio only","Prevalence at a single point in time","Incidence of disease","Case fatality of past cases"]$x$, 2, $x$In a cohort (prospective) study, initially disease-free exposed and unexposed groups are followed over time, so new cases can be counted to yield incidence and relative risk. Case-control studies cannot measure incidence directly.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (13, $x$Which bias is the most characteristic problem of case-control studies that rely on past exposure history?$x$, $x$["Ascertainment bias from randomization","Recall bias","Lead-time bias","Loss to follow-up bias"]$x$, 1, $x$Recall bias arises in case-control studies because cases tend to remember or report past exposures differently from controls, distorting the exposure-disease association. It is a form of information bias inherent to retrospective enquiry.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (14, $x$A confounding factor is one that is:$x$, $x$["An intermediate step in the causal pathway","Associated with both the exposure and the outcome","Present only in the exposed group by design","Randomly distributed and therefore always ignorable"]$x$, 1, $x$A confounder is independently associated with both the exposure and the disease outcome without being an intermediate in the causal chain, and it can distort the observed association. Age and smoking are common examples.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (15, $x$The main purpose of randomization in a randomized controlled trial is to:$x$, $x$["Guarantee exactly equal numbers in every subgroup","Distribute confounding factors equally between groups","Ensure the outcome is always positive","Eliminate the need for a control group"]$x$, 1, $x$Randomization allocates subjects to study groups by chance so that both known and unknown confounders are distributed equally between them. This removes selection bias and permits a valid comparison of the intervention effect.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (16, $x$In a case-control study, the measure used to estimate the strength of association between exposure and disease is the:$x$, $x$["Incidence rate","Odds ratio","Population attributable risk percent","Relative risk computed directly"]$x$, 1, $x$Case-control studies compare the odds of exposure in cases versus controls, yielding the odds ratio, which approximates relative risk when the disease is rare. Incidence and relative risk cannot be calculated directly from this design.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (17, $x$Selection bias in an epidemiological study refers to error arising from:$x$, $x$["Random misclassification of the outcome","Inaccurate measurement of the exposure","The manner in which study subjects are chosen","The play of chance in a small sample"]$x$, 2, $x$Selection bias occurs when the procedure used to select subjects produces study groups that differ systematically from the target population, distorting the exposure-outcome relationship. It is distinct from information (measurement) bias.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (18, $x$In cost-benefit analysis of a health programme, both the costs and the outcomes are expressed in:$x$, $x$["Life-years gained","Quality-adjusted life years","Number of cases prevented","Monetary units"]$x$, 3, $x$Cost-benefit analysis measures both inputs and consequences in money terms, allowing a direct judgement of whether benefits outweigh costs. Placing a monetary value on health outcomes is its distinguishing and most difficult feature.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (19, $x$Cost-effectiveness analysis differs from cost-benefit analysis because its outcomes are measured in:$x$, $x$["Rupees saved per patient","Return on investment ratios","Natural units such as cases prevented or life-years gained","Net present monetary value"]$x$, 2, $x$Cost-effectiveness analysis keeps costs in money but expresses outcomes in natural health units such as life-years gained or cases prevented, comparing interventions by cost per unit of effect. This avoids valuing health itself in money.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (20, $x$The health outcome measure that combines both length and quality of life, used in cost-utility analysis, is the:$x$, $x$["Quality-adjusted life year (QALY)","Standardized mortality ratio","Incidence density","Crude death rate"]$x$, 0, $x$Cost-utility analysis uses composite measures such as the QALY, or the DALY averted, which integrate the quantity and quality of life into a single index. This allows comparison of very different kinds of health interventions.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (21, $x$Which method of health financing places the greatest financial risk directly on the sick individual at the time of illness?$x$, $x$["Out-of-pocket payment","Community-based prepayment schemes","Social health insurance","Financing through general taxation"]$x$, 0, $x$Out-of-pocket payment requires patients to pay directly when they use services, providing no risk pooling and often causing catastrophic health expenditure. Insurance and tax-based systems spread the financial risk across many people.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (22, $x$Medical sociology is best defined as the study of:$x$, $x$["Microbial causes of communicable disease","Chemical treatment of mental disorders","The statistical distribution of diseases only","Social causes and consequences of health and illness"]$x$, 3, $x$Medical sociology studies the social factors that influence health, illness behaviour, and the organization of health care, along with the social consequences of disease. It highlights how culture, class, and society shape health.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (23, $x$The influence of social class on health is best illustrated by the observation that:$x$, $x$["Higher social classes always have poorer health","Social class has no measurable effect on mortality","Lower socio-economic groups generally have higher morbidity and mortality","Disease is distributed randomly across all classes"]$x$, 2, $x$Social class is a powerful determinant of health, and lower socio-economic groups consistently show higher morbidity and mortality owing to poorer living conditions, nutrition, and access to care. This social gradient in health is well documented.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (24, $x$In the context of health education, "IEC" stands for:$x$, $x$["International Epidemic Committee","Integrated Environmental Care","Immunization, Epidemiology and Control","Information, Education and Communication"]$x$, 3, $x$IEC stands for Information, Education and Communication, a strategy that combines these approaches to encourage people to adopt and sustain healthy practices. It is a central tool in health promotion programmes.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (25, $x$A key advantage of two-way communication over one-way communication in health education is that it:$x$, $x$["Provides feedback and allows clarification","Is always cheaper to organize","Eliminates the need for a communicator","Reaches larger audiences more quickly"]$x$, 0, $x$Two-way communication permits feedback, so the receiver can ask questions and the communicator can clarify and correct misunderstandings, making it more effective for changing behaviour. One-way methods reach many people but lack this interaction.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (26, $x$In the communication process, "noise" that distorts a health message is an example of a:$x$, $x$["Type of receiver","Channel of communication","Source of feedback","Barrier to communication"]$x$, 3, $x$Barriers to communication include physiological, psychological, environmental, and cultural factors, collectively termed noise, that distort or block the message between sender and receiver. Identifying them improves the effectiveness of health education.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (27, $x$In the Health Belief Model, the likelihood of a person taking preventive action depends primarily on:$x$, $x$["Perceived susceptibility, severity, benefits and barriers","The literacy level of the health worker only","Random chance unrelated to personal beliefs","The monetary cost of the service alone"]$x$, 0, $x$The Health Belief Model predicts health behaviour from perceived susceptibility to and severity of a condition, weighed against the perceived benefits and barriers of acting, often prompted by cues to action. It is widely applied in designing IEC.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (28, $x$Assessing whether a health programme achieved its intended long-term reduction in disease burden is an example of:$x$, $x$["Formative evaluation","Input evaluation","Impact (outcome) evaluation","Process evaluation"]$x$, 2, $x$Impact or outcome evaluation measures the extent to which a programme achieved its ultimate objectives, such as reduced morbidity or mortality. Process evaluation, by contrast, assesses how the activities were actually carried out.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (29, $x$The primary purpose of a Health Management Information System (HMIS) is to:$x$, $x$["Conduct laboratory diagnostic tests","Replace all clinical judgement with computers","Store only the financial accounts of a hospital","Provide relevant information to support health decision-making and management"]$x$, 3, $x$An HMIS collects, processes, and provides timely and relevant data so that managers and providers can plan, monitor, and evaluate health services and make evidence-based decisions. Data are collected for action, not merely for record-keeping.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$)
) as v(pos, question, options, ci, exp, topic, diff);

-- 29-community-schemes.txt — 30 questions
with b as (
  insert into tests (title, topic, difficulty, duration_minutes)
  values ($x$w3-community-e — ingested draft, verify before trusting$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, 'medium', 60)
  returning id
)
insert into questions (test_id, position, question, options, correct_index, explanation, topic, difficulty)
select b.id, v.pos::int, v.question, v.options::jsonb, v.ci::int, v.exp, v.topic, v.diff
from b, (values
  (0, $x$The rotavirus vaccine used in India's Universal Immunisation Programme is administered by which route?$x$, $x$["Oral","Intradermal","Intramuscular","Subcutaneous"]$x$, 0, $x$Rotavirus vaccine is a live attenuated oral vaccine given under UIP to prevent severe rotaviral diarrhoea. India uses indigenous vaccines such as Rotavac and Rotasiil.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (1, $x$How many doses of rotavirus vaccine are given under the Universal Immunisation Programme?$x$, $x$["Four","Three","Two","One"]$x$, 1, $x$Three doses of rotavirus vaccine are given orally at 6, 10 and 14 weeks along with pentavalent and OPV. It protects infants against severe gastroenteritis caused by rotavirus.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (2, $x$Under UIP, the pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (PCV) is scheduled at:$x$, $x$["Birth, 6 and 9 months","6 weeks, 14 weeks and 9 months","9 and 16 months","6, 10 and 14 weeks"]$x$, 1, $x$PCV follows a 2+1 schedule with primary doses at 6 and 14 weeks and a booster at 9 months. It protects against Streptococcus pneumoniae, a major cause of pneumonia and meningitis in children.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (3, $x$The correct route and site for administration of PCV is:$x$, $x$["Intramuscular in the anterolateral thigh","Intradermal over the forearm","Oral drops","Subcutaneous over the deltoid"]$x$, 0, $x$PCV is given intramuscularly in the anterolateral aspect of the mid-thigh as a 0.5 ml dose. India uses PCV13 in the immunisation programme.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (4, $x$Under UIP, fractional inactivated polio vaccine (fIPV) is administered as:$x$, $x$["A single subcutaneous dose at 9 months","Two intradermal doses of 0.1 ml at 6 and 14 weeks","Oral drops at 6, 10 and 14 weeks","A 0.5 ml intramuscular dose at 14 weeks only"]$x$, 1, $x$Fractional IPV is given as two intradermal doses of 0.1 ml at 6 and 14 weeks. It was introduced to boost population immunity against type 2 poliovirus as part of the polio endgame.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (5, $x$IPV was introduced into the Universal Immunisation Programme mainly as part of:$x$, $x$["The polio endgame strategy following the switch from tOPV to bOPV","The Mission Indradhanush deworming drive","Universal newborn screening","The measles-rubella elimination plan"]$x$, 0, $x$IPV was introduced in 2015-16 as part of the global polio endgame, preceding the April 2016 switch from trivalent to bivalent OPV. IPV maintains immunity against type 2 poliovirus, which was removed from OPV.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (6, $x$The Japanese encephalitis vaccine used in the Indian UIP is:$x$, $x$["An inactivated whole-virion vaccine given at birth","A conjugate vaccine given intramuscularly","The live attenuated SA 14-14-2 vaccine","A killed Vero cell vaccine given orally"]$x$, 2, $x$The live attenuated SA 14-14-2 JE vaccine is used in endemic districts and given subcutaneously. Campaign vaccination precedes its introduction into routine immunisation.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (7, $x$In endemic districts, the two routine doses of JE vaccine are scheduled at:$x$, $x$["Birth and 6 weeks","5 years and 10 years","9 months and 16-24 months","6 and 14 weeks"]$x$, 2, $x$The first routine JE dose is given at 9 completed months with measles-rubella, and the second at 16-24 months with the DPT booster. These are additional to any preceding campaign dose.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (8, $x$The HPV vaccine is recommended primarily for which group?$x$, $x$["Newborn infants","Pregnant women","Adolescent girls aged 9-14 years","Elderly women above 60 years"]$x$, 2, $x$HPV vaccine targets adolescent girls aged 9-14 years to prevent cervical cancer caused mainly by HPV types 16 and 18. India's indigenous vaccine, Cervavac, was launched in 2022.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (9, $x$For girls aged 9-14 years, the recommended HPV vaccination schedule is:$x$, $x$["Annual boosters lifelong","Five doses over five years","Two doses","A single mandatory dose only"]$x$, 2, $x$A two-dose schedule given about six months apart is recommended for girls aged 9-14 years. HPV prevents cervical cancer, the second most common cancer among Indian women.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (10, $x$The Rashtriya Kishor Swasthya Karyakram (RKSK) covers which age group?$x$, $x$["10-19 years","20-29 years","0-5 years","6-9 years"]$x$, 0, $x$RKSK, launched in 2014, addresses the health needs of adolescents aged 10-19 years. It reaches both boys and girls, in and out of school, married and unmarried.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (11, $x$Which of the following is NOT one of the six strategic priorities of RKSK?$x$, $x$["Sanitation and safe drinking water","Nutrition","Substance misuse","Mental health"]$x$, 0, $x$The six RKSK priorities are nutrition, sexual and reproductive health, non-communicable diseases, substance misuse, injuries and violence, and mental health. Sanitation is not a listed strategic priority.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (12, $x$Under RKSK, the trained peer educators who promote adolescent health are called:$x$, $x$["Saathiya","Anganwadi workers","ASHA","Saheli"]$x$, 0, $x$Peer educators under RKSK are called Saathiya and use the Saathiya Salah resource kit to guide adolescents. Adolescent Friendly Health Clinics form the facility-based component.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (13, $x$The Weekly Iron and Folic Acid Supplementation (WIFS) programme provides:$x$, $x$["Vitamin A to under-fives","Calcium tablets to the elderly","A weekly IFA tablet plus biannual deworming for adolescents","Daily iron for pregnant women"]$x$, 2, $x$WIFS provides a weekly supervised iron-folic acid tablet and biannual albendazole deworming to adolescents to combat anaemia. It covers school-going and out-of-school adolescents through schools and Anganwadi centres.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (14, $x$The Menstrual Hygiene Scheme mainly promotes sanitary napkin use among:$x$, $x$["Boys aged 10-19 years","Adolescent girls aged 10-19 years in rural areas","Pregnant women","Postmenopausal women"]$x$, 1, $x$The scheme, launched in 2011, promotes menstrual hygiene among rural adolescent girls aged 10-19 years. ASHAs assist in distribution and awareness generation.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (15, $x$Under the Menstrual Hygiene Scheme, subsidised sanitary napkins are distributed by ASHAs under the brand name:$x$, $x$["Freedays","Sakhi","Suvidha","Asmita"]$x$, 0, $x$Sanitary napkins under the national scheme are provided under the brand name Freedays. ASHAs receive an incentive for distribution and also get a free pack for personal use.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (16, $x$The National Programme for Health Care of the Elderly (NPHCE) targets persons aged:$x$, $x$["45 years and above","50 years and above","60 years and above","65 years and above"]$x$, 2, $x$NPHCE, launched in 2010-11, provides dedicated health care to persons aged 60 years and above. It establishes geriatric OPDs and Regional Geriatric Centres for specialised care.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (17, $x$A key facility established under NPHCE at identified medical colleges is the:$x$, $x$["Regional Geriatric Centre","Nutrition Rehabilitation Centre","Adolescent Friendly Health Clinic","District Early Intervention Centre"]$x$, 0, $x$NPHCE establishes Regional Geriatric Centres at selected medical colleges to provide specialist geriatric services and training. District hospitals run geriatric wards and OPDs.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (18, $x$The legislation that governs tobacco control in India, COTPA, was enacted in:$x$, $x$["1998","2003","2007","2011"]$x$, 1, $x$The Cigarettes and Other Tobacco Products Act (COTPA) was enacted in 2003. The National Tobacco Control Programme was launched in 2007-08 to enforce its provisions and reduce tobacco use.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (19, $x$Under COTPA, the sale of tobacco products is prohibited to persons below the age of:$x$, $x$["25 years","21 years","18 years","16 years"]$x$, 2, $x$COTPA prohibits sale of tobacco products to and by minors below 18 years and within 100 yards of educational institutions. It also bans smoking in public places and tobacco advertising.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (20, $x$The drug administered on National Deworming Day is:$x$, $x$["Albendazole","Praziquantel","Ivermectin","Metronidazole"]$x$, 0, $x$Albendazole is given on National Deworming Day to control soil-transmitted helminth infections. Children aged 1-2 years get 200 mg (half tablet) and those 2-19 years get 400 mg.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (21, $x$National Deworming Day targets children and adolescents aged:$x$, $x$["5 to 10 years","10 to 19 years only","6 months to 5 years","1 to 19 years"]$x$, 3, $x$National Deworming Day covers all children and adolescents aged 1-19 years, both in and out of school. It is observed biannually, typically on 10 February and 10 August.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (22, $x$POSHAN Abhiyaan primarily aims to reduce:$x$, $x$["Malaria transmission","Tobacco consumption","Road traffic injuries","Stunting, undernutrition, anaemia and low birth weight"]$x$, 3, $x$POSHAN Abhiyaan, the National Nutrition Mission launched in 2018, targets reduction of stunting, undernutrition, anaemia and low birth weight. It emphasises convergence, technology and a Jan Andolan (people's movement).$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (23, $x$POSHAN Abhiyaan set a target to reduce stunting at what annual rate?$x$, $x$["1% per year","2% per year","5% per year","10% per year"]$x$, 1, $x$POSHAN Abhiyaan aims to reduce stunting by 2% per year and undernutrition by 2% per year. It targets a 3% annual reduction in anaemia among the specified beneficiary groups.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (24, $x$The Anaemia Mukt Bharat strategy is popularly described as the:$x$, $x$["3-by-5 strategy","4-3-2 strategy","6x6x6 strategy","90-90-90 strategy"]$x$, 2, $x$Anaemia Mukt Bharat uses a 6x6x6 strategy: six beneficiary age groups, six interventions and six institutional mechanisms. Prophylactic iron-folic acid supplementation and deworming are central interventions.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (25, $x$Under Pradhan Mantri Surakshit Matritva Abhiyan (PMSMA), free antenatal check-ups are provided on which fixed day each month?$x$, $x$["1st of every month","9th of every month","15th of every month","Last day of every month"]$x$, 1, $x$PMSMA provides free, quality antenatal care on the 9th of every month to pregnant women in their 2nd and 3rd trimesters. Specialists and private practitioners are encouraged to volunteer for these clinics.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (26, $x$The LaQshya initiative aims to improve the quality of care in the:$x$, $x$["Adolescent health clinic","Immunisation clinic","Labour room and maternity operation theatre","Geriatric ward"]$x$, 2, $x$LaQshya, the Labour Room Quality Improvement Initiative launched in 2017, improves care during delivery and the immediate postpartum period. It aims to reduce maternal and newborn mortality and morbidity.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (27, $x$The Surakshit Matritva Aashwasan (SUMAN) initiative primarily assures:$x$, $x$["Zero-cost, dignified and quality maternal and newborn care","Old age pension for elderly women","Free schooling for adolescent girls","Free tobacco cessation therapy"]$x$, 0, $x$SUMAN, launched in 2019, assures every pregnant woman and newborn free, dignified, respectful and quality healthcare with zero tolerance for denial of services. It aims to end all preventable maternal and newborn deaths.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (28, $x$Janani Shishu Suraksha Karyakram (JSSK) entitles pregnant women to:$x$, $x$["Free HPV vaccination","Free delivery, drugs, diagnostics, diet, blood and transport","Old age health cards","A cash incentive only for institutional delivery"]$x$, 1, $x$JSSK, launched in 2011, entitles pregnant women and sick newborns to free delivery including caesarean, drugs, diagnostics, diet, blood and transport. It aims to eliminate out-of-pocket expenditure for institutional care.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (29, $x$Under JSSK, free treatment entitlements for sick infants were extended to cover infants up to the age of:$x$, $x$["6 months","28 days","1 year","7 days"]$x$, 2, $x$JSSK entitlements for sick newborns were extended to cover all sick infants up to one year of age. This includes free treatment, drugs, diagnostics and transport, reducing the financial burden on families.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$)
) as v(pos, question, options, ci, exp, topic, diff);

-- 30-community-environment.txt — 30 questions
with b as (
  insert into tests (title, topic, difficulty, duration_minutes)
  values ($x$w3-community-f — ingested draft, verify before trusting$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, 'medium', 60)
  returning id
)
insert into questions (test_id, position, question, options, correct_index, explanation, topic, difficulty)
select b.id, v.pos::int, v.question, v.options::jsonb, v.ci::int, v.exp, v.topic, v.diff
from b, (values
  (0, $x$Which larvicide is recommended by WHO as safe for treatment of potable (drinking) water against mosquito larvae?$x$, $x$["Paris green","Temephos","DDT","Malathion"]$x$, 1, $x$Temephos (Abate) is an organophosphorus larvicide with very low mammalian toxicity, so it is the only larvicide approved for use in drinking water sources. It is applied to control mosquito larvae in wells and storage tanks.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (1, $x$The larvivorous fish most widely used in India for mosquito control is:$x$, $x$["Labeo rohita","Gambusia affinis","Hilsa","Catla catla"]$x$, 1, $x$Gambusia affinis and Poecilia (Lebistes) reticulata (guppy) are the classical larvivorous fish used in biological control. They feed on mosquito larvae in ponds, wells and ornamental water bodies, reducing anopheline breeding.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (2, $x$For drinking water, the coliform (E. coli) count should be:$x$, $x$["50 per 100 mL","100 per 100 mL","10 per 100 mL","0 per 100 mL"]$x$, 3, $x$Safe drinking water must contain zero coliform organisms in any 100 mL sample throughout the year. The coliform group, especially E. coli, is used as the indicator of recent faecal contamination.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (3, $x$In indoor residual spraying (IRS), the classical insecticide that has been used for decades is:$x$, $x$["Temephos","Paris green","DDT","Pyrethrum"]$x$, 2, $x$DDT, an organochlorine, has been the classical residual insecticide sprayed on interior wall surfaces to kill resting adult mosquitoes. Its long residual action on sprayed surfaces made it central to malaria control programmes.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (4, $x$Long-lasting insecticidal nets (LLINs) are usually impregnated with:$x$, $x$["Carbamates","Organophosphates","Organochlorines","Synthetic pyrethroids"]$x$, 3, $x$LLINs are factory-treated with synthetic pyrethroids such as deltamethrin or permethrin, which repel and kill mosquitoes. The insecticide is incorporated into or coated on the fibres to retain efficacy over many washes.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (5, $x$Fresh bleaching powder used for water disinfection contains available chlorine of about:$x$, $x$["10%","33%","50%","20%"]$x$, 1, $x$Fresh, good-quality bleaching powder (calcium hypochlorite) contains about 33 percent available chlorine. On exposure to air, light and moisture it deteriorates and loses chlorine, so it must be stored in dark, airtight containers.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (6, $x$The Bangalore method is a technique of:$x$, $x$["Water filtration","Chlorination of water","Composting of refuse and night soil","Vector control"]$x$, 2, $x$The Bangalore method is an anaerobic composting technique in which alternate layers of refuse and night soil are placed in a trench and covered with earth. It converts waste into manure and is also called the hot fermentation process.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (7, $x$Turbidity of drinking water is measured and expressed in:$x$, $x$["ppm","mg/L","MPN","NTU"]$x$, 3, $x$Turbidity is a physical parameter measured in Nephelometric Turbidity Units (NTU). As per BIS the acceptable limit is 1 NTU and the permissible limit is 5 NTU in the absence of an alternate source.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (8, $x$As per BIS, the desirable (acceptable) limit of total dissolved solids in drinking water is:$x$, $x$["1000 mg/L","2000 mg/L","250 mg/L","500 mg/L"]$x$, 3, $x$The desirable limit of total dissolved solids is 500 mg/L, with a maximum permissible limit of 2000 mg/L when no alternate source exists. High TDS affects palatability and may indicate excess salts or hardness.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (9, $x$The minimum recommended free residual chlorine in disinfected water after one hour of contact is:$x$, $x$["0.1 mg/L","0.5 mg/L","1.0 mg/L","2.0 mg/L"]$x$, 1, $x$A free residual chlorine of 0.5 mg/L after a contact period of one hour is the accepted criterion of adequate disinfection. This residual provides a safety margin against recontamination in the distribution system.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (10, $x$Horrock's apparatus is used in the field to determine:$x$, $x$["Amount of dissolved oxygen","Dose of bleaching powder needed for water","Total hardness","Turbidity of water"]$x$, 1, $x$Horrock's apparatus is a simple field kit used to find the correct dose of bleaching powder required to disinfect a given volume of water. It works by determining the chlorine demand of the water sample.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (11, $x$The "vital layer" (schmutzdecke), a slimy biological layer responsible for purification, is a feature of the:$x$, $x$["Reverse osmosis unit","Rapid sand filter","Pressure filter","Slow sand filter"]$x$, 3, $x$In the slow sand (biological) filter, a slimy zoogleal layer called the schmutzdecke forms on the top of the sand bed. This vital layer removes organic matter and bacteria, giving a purification efficiency of about 99.9 percent.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (12, $x$The Most Probable Number (MPN) test of a water sample estimates the number of:$x$, $x$["Free chlorine molecules","Hardness salts","Coliform organisms","Turbidity particles"]$x$, 2, $x$The MPN or presumptive coliform test statistically estimates the number of coliform organisms per 100 mL of water. It is a key bacteriological examination used to assess faecal pollution and the safety of drinking water.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (13, $x$Paris green is an effective larvicide against anopheline larvae mainly because these larvae are:$x$, $x$["Bottom feeders","Filter feeders","Surface feeders","Predators"]$x$, 2, $x$Paris green (copper aceto-arsenite) is a stomach poison that floats on the water surface as a fine dust. Because anopheline larvae feed at the surface, they ingest the particles, whereas culicine larvae that feed lower down are less affected.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (14, $x$In vector control, "source reduction" refers to:$x$, $x$["Spraying insecticide on indoor walls","Releasing larvivorous fish","Elimination or reduction of vector breeding places","Distribution of bed nets"]$x$, 2, $x$Source reduction is an environmental method that removes or modifies mosquito breeding places, such as filling ditches, draining stagnant water and proper water storage. By attacking the source, it prevents larvae from developing.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (15, $x$According to Pettenkofer, air in an occupied room is considered adequately ventilated if the carbon dioxide concentration does not exceed:$x$, $x$["60 per 1000","0.6 per 1000","6 per 1000","0.03 per 1000"]$x$, 1, $x$Pettenkofer proposed that the CO2 level should not rise above 0.6 parts per 1000 (0.6 per mille) of air. CO2 itself is not harmful at these levels but serves as an index of the vitiation of indoor air by occupants.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (16, $x$For prevention of overcrowding, a floor space of 100 sq ft or more per room is considered adequate for:$x$, $x$["1.5 persons","1 person","3 persons","2 persons"]$x$, 3, $x$By the floor-space standard, a room of 100 sq ft or more is allotted for two persons; 70-100 sq ft for 1.5, and 50-70 sq ft for one person. Falling below these values constitutes overcrowding.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (17, $x$As per BIS, the desirable (acceptable) limit of fluoride in drinking water is:$x$, $x$["0.5 mg/L","1.0 mg/L","1.5 mg/L","2.0 mg/L"]$x$, 1, $x$The desirable fluoride limit is 1.0 mg/L, with a maximum permissible limit of 1.5 mg/L. Levels below 0.5 mg/L predispose to dental caries, whereas levels above 1.5 mg/L cause dental and skeletal fluorosis.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (18, $x$The Indore method of composting is essentially a/an:$x$, $x$["Incineration process","Chemical process","Anaerobic process","Aerobic process"]$x$, 3, $x$The Indore method, developed by Howard and Wad, is an aerobic composting process in which refuse and night soil are stacked and periodically turned to allow air entry. Aerobic decomposition yields manure in about four months.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (19, $x$The Rideal-Walker coefficient (phenol coefficient) is used to test the efficacy of:$x$, $x$["Vaccines","Larvicides","Antibiotics","Disinfectants"]$x$, 3, $x$The Rideal-Walker or phenol coefficient compares the germicidal power of a disinfectant with that of phenol under standard conditions. A coefficient greater than one indicates the disinfectant is more potent than phenol.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (20, $x$The kata thermometer is used to measure the:$x$, $x$["Radiant heat load","Atmospheric pressure","Relative humidity","Cooling power of air and low air velocities"]$x$, 3, $x$The kata thermometer measures the cooling power of air by timing how long it takes to cool between two fixed temperatures. It is especially useful for estimating the low air velocities relevant to ventilation and thermal comfort.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (21, $x$Which organism is regarded as the best bacteriological indicator of recent faecal pollution of water?$x$, $x$["Escherichia coli","Clostridium perfringens","Streptococcus faecalis","Vibrio cholerae"]$x$, 0, $x$Escherichia coli is the best indicator of recent faecal pollution because it is abundant in human faeces and does not multiply appreciably in water. Its presence signals contamination and the possible presence of enteric pathogens.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (22, $x$As per BIS, the permissible (maximum) limit of total hardness as CaCO3 in the absence of an alternate source is:$x$, $x$["200 mg/L","300 mg/L","600 mg/L","1000 mg/L"]$x$, 2, $x$The desirable limit of total hardness is 200 mg/L, extendable to a permissible maximum of 600 mg/L when no alternate source is available. Excess hardness causes scale formation and increased soap consumption.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (23, $x$The WHO-recommended dose of temephos for treatment of potable water against mosquito larvae is:$x$, $x$["5 mg/L","1 mg/L","50 mg/L","10 mg/L"]$x$, 1, $x$Temephos is applied at a dose of about 1 mg/L (1 ppm) in potable water, a concentration that is larvicidal yet safe for human consumption. Its low toxicity is what permits its use in drinking water sources.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (24, $x$The IMViC test is used mainly to:$x$, $x$["Estimate water hardness","Differentiate faecal from non-faecal coliforms","Measure turbidity","Detect chlorine demand"]$x$, 1, $x$The IMViC series (Indole, Methyl red, Voges-Proskauer, Citrate) helps distinguish faecal coliforms like E. coli from non-faecal coliforms of soil or plant origin. This confirms whether coliforms detected in water are of faecal significance.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (25, $x$The index "effective temperature," used to assess thermal comfort, integrates air temperature, air movement and:$x$, $x$["Humidity","Barometric pressure","CO2 concentration","Illumination"]$x$, 0, $x$Effective temperature combines dry-bulb temperature, air movement and humidity into a single index of the sensation of warmth. It is used to define the comfort zone within which most people feel thermally comfortable.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (26, $x$In the Bangalore method of composting, decomposition of the waste is:$x$, $x$["Anaerobic and ready in two weeks","Aerobic and ready in four to six months","Aerobic and ready in two weeks","Anaerobic and ready in about four to six months"]$x$, 3, $x$In the Bangalore (hot fermentation) method the buried alternate layers of refuse and night soil undergo anaerobic decomposition. Satisfactory manure is obtained in about four to six months, and the closed pit reduces fly breeding and odour.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (27, $x$"Break-point chlorination" refers to the stage at which:$x$, $x$["Water becomes turbid","Coliforms first appear","Chlorine demand is fully met and free residual chlorine begins to appear","All hardness is removed"]$x$, 2, $x$The break point is where added chlorine has satisfied the entire chlorine demand, oxidising organic matter and ammonia, after which free residual chlorine begins to appear. Chlorinating to this point ensures reliable disinfection.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (28, $x$In indoor residual spraying for malaria control, the usual dose of DDT applied to wall surfaces is:$x$, $x$["10 g/m2","25 g/m2","0.1 g/m2","1-2 g/m2"]$x$, 3, $x$DDT is sprayed at a dose of 1-2 g per square metre of wall surface, giving a residual effect that lasts roughly 6 to 12 weeks. The insecticide kills adult mosquitoes that rest on treated surfaces after feeding.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (29, $x$In controlled tipping (sanitary landfill), after the refuse is compacted and covered with earth, the temperature within the fill rises to about:$x$, $x$["30 degrees C","100 degrees C","40 degrees C","60 degrees C"]$x$, 3, $x$In a sanitary landfill, biological and chemical action raises the internal temperature to around 60 degrees C within a few days. This heat destroys pathogens and hastens decomposition, while the earth cover controls flies and odour.$x$, $x$Community Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$)
) as v(pos, question, options, ci, exp, topic, diff);

-- 31-foundations-procedures.txt — 29 questions
with b as (
  insert into tests (title, topic, difficulty, duration_minutes)
  values ($x$w3-foundations-c — ingested draft, verify before trusting$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, 'medium', 60)
  returning id
)
insert into questions (test_id, position, question, options, correct_index, explanation, topic, difficulty)
select b.id, v.pos::int, v.question, v.options::jsonb, v.ci::int, v.exp, v.topic, v.diff
from b, (values
  (0, $x$When several blood specimens are drawn with the evacuated (vacutainer) tube system, which container should be filled first to prevent additive cross-contamination?$x$, $x$["Gray-top (fluoride) tube","Blood culture bottle","Lavender-top (EDTA) tube","Light-blue-top (citrate) tube"]$x$, 1, $x$The recommended order of draw places the sterile blood culture first, then coagulation (light blue), serum, heparin, EDTA, and finally fluoride tubes. Drawing cultures first preserves sterility and prevents additive carryover that would alter later test results.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (1, $x$The main reason for obtaining a midstream "clean-catch" urine specimen is to:$x$, $x$["Measure total urinary output accurately","Collect urine that is relatively free of external contaminants for culture","Determine the exact urine specific gravity","Capture the very first portion of the urinary stream"]$x$, 1, $x$Cleaning the meatus and collecting the middle portion of the stream flushes away external organisms, giving a specimen that reflects bladder urine. This makes the culture result more reliable for diagnosing a urinary tract infection.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (2, $x$When starting a 24-hour urine collection, the nurse should:$x$, $x$["Collect every specimen in a separate sterile container","Save the first voided specimen and record it as the start","Discard the first voided specimen and begin timing from then","Refrigerate only the last specimen of the period"]$x$, 2, $x$Timed collections begin with an empty bladder, so the first void is discarded and the clock starts at that moment. All subsequent urine, including a final void at the end of 24 hours, is saved and usually kept cool or on ice.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (3, $x$A stool specimen collected to detect ova and parasites should be:$x$, $x$["Delivered to the laboratory while still warm and fresh","Mixed with tap water before transport","Frozen for 24 hours before analysis","Collected only after an oil-retention enema"]$x$, 0, $x$Trophozoites of parasites are best identified in a fresh, warm stool because motility and morphology deteriorate on cooling. The specimen must not be contaminated with urine, water, or toilet tissue, which can destroy or obscure organisms.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (4, $x$The most appropriate time to collect a sputum specimen for laboratory examination is:$x$, $x$["Immediately following a meal","After the client rinses with antiseptic mouthwash","Right before the client goes to sleep","Early in the morning on awakening"]$x$, 3, $x$Secretions accumulate in the airways overnight, so an early-morning cough yields the most concentrated, representative sputum. The client should rinse with plain water rather than mouthwash and cough deeply from the lungs, not expectorate saliva.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (5, $x$When obtaining a throat swab for culture, the nurse should firmly swab the:$x$, $x$["Anterior two-thirds of the tongue","Hard palate and gum line","Tonsillar areas and posterior pharyngeal wall","Inner cheeks and buccal mucosa"]$x$, 2, $x$Pathogens such as group A streptococci localize on the tonsils and posterior pharynx, so both tonsillar arches and the back of the throat are swabbed. The tongue, cheeks, and lips are avoided to prevent contamination with normal oral flora.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (6, $x$Which type of wound débridement relies on the body's own enzymes and moisture, retained by a moisture-retentive dressing, to liquefy necrotic tissue?$x$, $x$["Mechanical débridement","Autolytic débridement","Sharp (surgical) débridement","Enzymatic débridement"]$x$, 1, $x$Autolytic débridement uses occlusive or semi-occlusive dressings to trap wound fluid so endogenous enzymes can soften and separate dead tissue. It is selective and painless but slow, making it unsuitable for infected or heavily necrotic wounds needing rapid removal.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (7, $x$A hydrocolloid dressing is most appropriate for a wound that is:$x$, $x$["A deep tunneling wound with exposed bone","Clean and dry to lightly exudating, requiring a moist environment","Heavily draining and infected","In need of hourly visual inspection"]$x$, 1, $x$Hydrocolloid dressings form a gel with wound exudate and maintain a moist, occlusive environment that supports granulation and autolytic débridement. They suit wounds with minimal to moderate drainage, not heavily exudating or clinically infected wounds.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (8, $x$A wet-to-dry gauze dressing accomplishes débridement by:$x$, $x$["Delivering topical collagenase to the wound bed","Trapping debris in gauze that adheres as it dries and is then removed","Sealing the wound to promote autolysis","Applying continuous negative pressure"]$x$, 1, $x$Moist gauze is applied and allowed to dry so that necrotic tissue and exudate adhere to it; removing the dried gauze mechanically pulls away the debris. Because this is nonselective, it can also strip healthy granulation tissue and cause pain on removal.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (9, $x$A Penrose drain is best described as a:$x$, $x$["Rigid tube used exclusively for pleural drainage","Soft, open drain that permits passive drainage onto a dressing","Self-contained bulb suction system","Closed device attached to continuous wall suction"]$x$, 1, $x$A Penrose is a flat, soft rubber tube that provides passive drainage by capillary action and gravity into an absorbent dressing. A sterile safety pin is often attached to the outer end to prevent the drain from slipping into the wound.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (10, $x$Continuous bubbling in the water-seal chamber of a closed chest drainage system most likely indicates:$x$, $x$["Normal, expected functioning of the system","Complete re-expansion of the lung","An air leak somewhere in the system","A clot obstructing the chest tube"]$x$, 2, $x$Intermittent bubbling or tidaling in the water-seal chamber is normal, but continuous bubbling signals that air is entering the system from the pleural space or a loose connection. The nurse should check all connections and the insertion site to locate the leak.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (11, $x$Which cluster of findings at a peripheral IV site best indicates infiltration?$x$, $x$["Purulent drainage with fever","A red streak and palpable cord along the vein","Swelling, coolness, and pallor with a slowed infusion","Distended neck veins and bounding pulse"]$x$, 2, $x$Infiltration occurs when IV fluid leaks into surrounding tissue, producing localized swelling, coolness, blanching, and often a decreased or stopped flow with no blood return. Warmth, redness, and a palpable cord instead suggest phlebitis.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (12, $x$The classic signs of phlebitis at a peripheral IV site are:$x$, $x$["A cold, hard, edematous area","Sudden dyspnea and chest pain","Redness, warmth, and tenderness along the course of the vein","Coolness, pallor, and blanching of the skin"]$x$, 2, $x$Phlebitis is inflammation of the vein wall and presents with erythema, warmth, tenderness, and sometimes a palpable venous cord. Management includes discontinuing the IV, applying warm compresses, and restarting the line at a different site.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (13, $x$If air embolism is suspected during central or IV therapy, the nurse should immediately position the client:$x$, $x$["In high Fowler's position","Sitting upright and leaning forward","On the left side in Trendelenburg (head-down) position","Prone with the head turned to one side"]$x$, 2, $x$The left lateral Trendelenburg position traps air in the right atrium and ventricle away from the pulmonary outflow, allowing it to be absorbed gradually. Oxygen is given and the physician notified, while the catheter is clamped to prevent further air entry.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (14, $x$A transparent semipermeable dressing covering a peripheral IV site should be changed when it:$x$, $x$["The client reports mild thirst","Has been in place for exactly 12 hours","Is replaced every time a new bag of fluid is hung","Becomes damp, loosened, or visibly soiled"]$x$, 3, $x$Transparent dressings are changed when their integrity is compromised, that is, when they are wet, loose, or soiled, or with catheter replacement per policy. Intact transparent dressings also allow continuous inspection of the site for early signs of complications.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (15, $x$Which practice is a core element of the central-line bundle for preventing catheter-associated bloodstream infection?$x$, $x$["Selecting the femoral vein preferentially in adults","Hand hygiene and chlorhexidine skin antisepsis with maximal barrier precautions","Leaving catheter hubs uncapped for quicker access","Routinely replacing the catheter every 24 hours"]$x$, 1, $x$The CLABSI prevention bundle emphasizes hand hygiene, chlorhexidine skin preparation, maximal sterile barriers at insertion, optimal site selection avoiding the femoral vein, and daily review of line necessity. Routine scheduled replacement of central lines is not recommended.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (16, $x$To help prevent catheter-associated urinary tract infection, the urinary drainage bag should be kept:$x$, $x$["Below the level of the bladder at all times","Above the level of the bladder","Level with the client's chest","Clamped except at scheduled voiding times"]$x$, 0, $x$Positioning the bag below the bladder uses gravity to keep urine flowing downward and prevents reflux of contaminated urine back into the bladder. The tubing should also be kept free of dependent loops and the closed drainage system maintained.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (17, $x$Before removing an indwelling urinary catheter, the nurse must first:$x$, $x$["Completely deflate the retention balloon by aspirating with a syringe","Cut the inflation valve to release the water","Clamp the catheter for a full 24 hours","Instill sterile saline to expand the balloon"]$x$, 0, $x$The balloon must be fully deflated by withdrawing all the sterile water with a syringe so it returns to catheter size for atraumatic removal. Cutting the inflation port is unreliable and may leave the balloon partly inflated, causing urethral trauma.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (18, $x$A healthy, well-perfused colostomy stoma normally appears:$x$, $x$["Dusky blue to black","White and firm","Pale pink and dry","Pink to red and moist"]$x$, 3, $x$A viable stoma is pink to brick-red and moist, reflecting a good blood supply, and it may bleed slightly when cleaned. A dark, dusky, or black stoma indicates ischemia and must be reported to the surgeon immediately.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (19, $x$When cutting the skin barrier of a colostomy appliance, the opening should be approximately:$x$, $x$["About 3 mm (1/8 inch) larger than the stoma","Slightly smaller than the stoma to grip it","Exactly the same size as the stoma","Twice the diameter of the stoma"]$x$, 0, $x$An opening about 1/8 inch larger than the stoma protects the surrounding skin from effluent while avoiding constriction of the stoma. An opening that is too large exposes skin to irritating output, and one that is too small can injure the stoma.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (20, $x$During tracheostomy suctioning, negative pressure should be applied:$x$, $x$["Only while advancing the catheter downward","Only while withdrawing the catheter, for no more than 10-15 seconds","For at least 30 seconds to remove all secretions","Continuously during both insertion and withdrawal"]$x$, 1, $x$Suction is applied intermittently only as the catheter is withdrawn, limiting each pass to about 10-15 seconds to minimize hypoxia and mucosal trauma. The client is hyperoxygenated before and after, and suctioning on insertion would needlessly remove oxygen.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (21, $x$Which items must always be kept at the bedside of a client with a new tracheostomy for emergency use?$x$, $x$["The obturator and a spare tracheostomy tube of the same size","A rigid oral airway and tongue depressor","A chest tube insertion tray","A pair of sterile suture scissors"]$x$, 0, $x$If the tube is accidentally dislodged, the obturator is needed to reinsert a tube, and a spare tube of the same size (and one smaller) allows prompt reestablishment of the airway. These, along with suction equipment, are essential bedside emergency supplies.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (22, $x$The correct way to estimate the length of nasogastric tube to insert is to measure from the:$x$, $x$["Mouth to the mid-sternum","Chin to the iliac crest","Tip of the nose to the earlobe to the xiphoid process","Tip of the nose to the umbilicus"]$x$, 2, $x$The NEX measurement (nose to earlobe to xiphoid) approximates the distance to the stomach and is marked on the tube before insertion. Placement is then confirmed by aspirate pH testing and, definitively, by radiography before the tube is used.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (23, $x$When a high gastric residual volume is aspirated before an intermittent NG feeding, the nurse should initially:$x$, $x$["Flush with 500 mL of water and continue as scheduled","Immediately remove the nasogastric tube","Hold the feeding, reassess, and follow facility protocol","Discard the aspirate and double the next feeding"]$x$, 2, $x$A high residual may indicate delayed gastric emptying and increased aspiration risk, so the feeding is held and the client reassessed per protocol before resuming. Aspirated contents are usually returned rather than discarded to avoid loss of electrolytes and gastric fluid.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (24, $x$Local application of cold produces which physiological effect?$x$, $x$["Vasodilation with increased blood flow","Vasoconstriction with reduced swelling and bleeding","Raised local tissue metabolism","Increased capillary permeability"]$x$, 1, $x$Cold causes vasoconstriction, which decreases blood flow, edema, bleeding, and inflammation, and it reduces pain by slowing nerve conduction. It is therefore useful in the early management of sprains and other acute injuries.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (25, $x$The "rebound phenomenon" seen with prolonged heat application means that, after maximum vasodilation at about 20-30 minutes, continued application causes:$x$, $x$["Vasodilation to keep increasing indefinitely","Complete cessation of blood flow to the part","The skin to become permanently anesthetized","The blood vessels to begin constricting (the opposite effect)"]$x$, 3, $x$Tissues reach their maximal therapeutic response after roughly 20-30 minutes, after which the reverse (rebound) effect begins and vessels constrict despite continued heat. Because of this, heat applications are time-limited to preserve benefit and prevent tissue injury.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (26, $x$A T-binder is most commonly used to:$x$, $x$["Hold dressings in place over the perineum or rectal area","Immobilize a fractured clavicle","Support pendulous breasts","Support the abdomen after abdominal surgery"]$x$, 0, $x$The T-binder (single-tail for females, double-tail for males) secures perineal, rectal, or genital dressings that are otherwise difficult to keep in place. A straight abdominal binder, by contrast, is used to support the abdomen and a surgical incision.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (27, $x$During gastric lavage for poisoning, the client is best positioned in the:$x$, $x$["Right lateral position with the head elevated","High Fowler's upright position","Left lateral position, often with the head slightly lowered","Supine position with the head of the bed flat"]$x$, 2, $x$The left lateral position with a slight head-down tilt keeps the pylorus uppermost, slowing passage of stomach contents into the duodenum and reducing aspiration risk. A protected airway is essential, and obtunded clients may require endotracheal intubation before lavage.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (28, $x$Which nursing action is part of performing last offices (care of the body after death)?$x$, $x$["Positioning the body in alignment and closing the eyes before rigor mortis develops","Elevating the head of the bed to a 90-degree angle","Removing all identification tags from the body","Leaving the dentures out and the mouth open"]$x$, 0, $x$Last offices include straightening the body in natural supine alignment, closing the eyes and mouth, and inserting dentures before rigor mortis sets in, usually within 2-4 hours. Identification is verified and kept in place, and the body is cleaned and made presentable for the family.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$)
) as v(pos, question, options, ci, exp, topic, diff);

-- 32-foundations-professional.txt — 30 questions
with b as (
  insert into tests (title, topic, difficulty, duration_minutes)
  values ($x$w3-foundations-d — ingested draft, verify before trusting$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, 'medium', 60)
  returning id
)
insert into questions (test_id, position, question, options, correct_index, explanation, topic, difficulty)
select b.id, v.pos::int, v.question, v.options::jsonb, v.ci::int, v.exp, v.topic, v.diff
from b, (values
  (0, $x$In which year was Florence Nightingale born?$x$, $x$["1810","1820","1830","1840"]$x$, 1, $x$Florence Nightingale was born on 12 May 1820 in Florence, Italy. She is regarded as the founder of modern nursing, and her birthday is celebrated worldwide as International Nurses Day.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (1, $x$Which famous book was written by Florence Nightingale?$x$, $x$["Gray's Anatomy","Textbook of Medicine","Principles of Surgery","Notes on Nursing"]$x$, 3, $x$Florence Nightingale wrote "Notes on Nursing: What It Is and What It Is Not" in 1859. It outlined her ideas on patient care and the environment and is considered a foundational nursing text.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (2, $x$Florence Nightingale is popularly remembered by which title?$x$, $x$["Sister of Mercy","The First Matron","The Lady with the Lamp","Mother of India"]$x$, 2, $x$She earned the title "The Lady with the Lamp" for making night rounds to care for wounded soldiers during the Crimean War. This image came to symbolize compassionate nursing care.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (3, $x$During which war did Florence Nightingale gain fame for organizing the care of wounded soldiers?$x$, $x$["Boer War","American Civil War","Crimean War","World War I"]$x$, 2, $x$Nightingale served at Scutari during the Crimean War (1853-1856), where she sharply reduced mortality by improving sanitation and hygiene. Her work established the value of trained nursing and environmental reform.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (4, $x$Communication conveyed through gestures, posture, and facial expressions is called:$x$, $x$["Non-verbal communication","Written communication","Verbal communication","Formal communication"]$x$, 0, $x$Non-verbal communication transmits messages without words, using body language, gestures, eye contact, and facial expressions. It often conveys emotions more accurately than spoken words.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (5, $x$Florence Nightingale's Environmental Theory primarily focuses on:$x$, $x$["Manipulating the environment to promote healing","Genetic counselling of patients","Complex surgical techniques","Advanced pharmacological therapy"]$x$, 0, $x$Nightingale's theory holds that a clean, well-ventilated, and calm environment supports the patient's natural reparative processes. The nurse's role is to alter the environment to promote recovery.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (6, $x$Which of the following is NOT one of the major environmental components emphasized in Nightingale's theory?$x$, $x$["Pure fresh air","Genetic inheritance","Pure water","Adequate light"]$x$, 1, $x$Nightingale identified factors such as pure air, pure water, efficient drainage, cleanliness, and light as essential to health. Genetic inheritance was not part of her environmental framework.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (7, $x$Which of the following is a characteristic of a profession?$x$, $x$["Complete lack of autonomy","A specialized body of knowledge and a code of ethics","Absence of a code of ethics","No systematic body of knowledge"]$x$, 1, $x$A profession is characterized by a unique body of knowledge, prolonged specialized education, a code of ethics, autonomy, and a service orientation. Nursing meets these criteria as a profession.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (8, $x$The International Council of Nurses (ICN), the first international professional nursing organization, was founded in:$x$, $x$["1912","1949","1899","1923"]$x$, 2, $x$The ICN was established in 1899, making it one of the oldest international professional organizations. It works to advance nursing standards, welfare, and health policy worldwide.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (9, $x$The basic elements of the communication process include:$x$, $x$["Sender, message, channel, receiver, and feedback","Only the sender and the receiver","Only feedback and silence","Only the message and noise"]$x$, 0, $x$Effective communication involves a sender who encodes a message, a channel or medium, a receiver who decodes it, and feedback. Barriers or "noise" may interfere at any stage of this process.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (10, $x$A noisy environment that interferes with the transmission of a message is an example of a:$x$, $x$["Encoding process","Feedback loop","Communication barrier","Communication channel"]$x$, 2, $x$Anything that distorts or blocks the message, such as noise, language differences, or strong emotions, is a communication barrier. Recognizing barriers helps the nurse improve clarity and understanding.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (11, $x$Which of the following is a therapeutic communication technique?$x$, $x$["Active listening","Giving false reassurance","Changing the subject","Giving unsolicited advice"]$x$, 0, $x$Active listening, using silence, reflection, and open-ended questions are therapeutic techniques that encourage the patient to express feelings. False reassurance and advice-giving are non-therapeutic responses.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (12, $x$Teaching a patient the skill of self-administering an insulin injection primarily involves which domain of learning?$x$, $x$["Affective domain","Psychomotor domain","Cognitive domain","Emotional domain"]$x$, 1, $x$The psychomotor domain involves the development of manual or physical skills requiring coordination. Learning to give an injection is a psychomotor skill practised through demonstration and return demonstration.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (13, $x$Which of the following is a method of health teaching?$x$, $x$["Stethoscope","Lecture and demonstration","Thermometer","Syringe"]$x$, 1, $x$Lecture, group discussion, demonstration, and role play are recognized methods of health teaching. Instruments such as the stethoscope and thermometer are clinical tools, not teaching methods.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (14, $x$The three domains of learning described by Benjamin Bloom are:$x$, $x$["Reading, writing, and arithmetic","Cognitive, affective, and psychomotor","Physical, mental, and social","Sensory, motor, and verbal"]$x$, 1, $x$Bloom's taxonomy classifies learning into cognitive (knowledge), affective (attitudes), and psychomotor (skills) domains. Nurse educators frame their teaching objectives around all three domains.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (15, $x$Learning that involves knowledge, comprehension, and intellectual skills belongs to which domain?$x$, $x$["Behavioural domain","Cognitive domain","Affective domain","Psychomotor domain"]$x$, 1, $x$The cognitive domain deals with mental processes such as knowledge, comprehension, application, analysis, synthesis, and evaluation. It is concerned with intellectual understanding and thinking.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (16, $x$Which data-collection tool is MOST appropriate for measuring the intensity or degree of a person's attitude along a continuum?$x$, $x$["Anecdotal record","Structured interview schedule","Observation checklist","Rating scale"]$x$, 3, $x$A rating scale allows the respondent or observer to judge an attribute along an ordered continuum, such as a Likert scale. It is well suited for quantifying attitudes, opinions, or the degree of a quality.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (17, $x$The affective domain of learning is primarily concerned with:$x$, $x$["Factual recall of information","Physical coordination","Attitudes, values, and emotions","Manual skills and dexterity"]$x$, 2, $x$The affective domain addresses feelings, attitudes, values, interests, and appreciation. Changing a patient's attitude toward adopting a healthy lifestyle is an example of an affective learning objective.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (18, $x$Which of the following is an audio-visual aid used in health teaching?$x$, $x$["Flannelgraph","Television or film","Printed pamphlet","Blackboard"]$x$, 1, $x$Audio-visual aids combine both sound and image, such as television, films, and videos. Pamphlets, blackboards, and flannelgraphs are considered visual aids only.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (19, $x$The primary purpose of maintaining nursing records and reports is to:$x$, $x$["Increase unnecessary paperwork","Ensure continuity of care and communication among the team","Replace all verbal communication permanently","Reduce the accountability of staff"]$x$, 1, $x$Records and reports provide a continuous account of the patient's condition and care, ensuring communication and continuity among health team members. They also serve legal, educational, and research purposes.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (20, $x$With respect to their legal value, patient records:$x$, $x$["Are meant only for decoration","Have no legal significance","Cannot be produced in a court of law","Serve as legal documents and admissible evidence"]$x$, 3, $x$Patient records are legal documents that can be used as evidence in a court of law. Accurate, complete, and timely documentation protects both the patient and the nurse in legal matters.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (21, $x$The nursing care plan is developed on the basis of which framework?$x$, $x$["The administrative hierarchy","Hospital financial planning","The purely medical model","The nursing process"]$x$, 3, $x$The nursing care plan is structured around the steps of the nursing process: assessment, diagnosis, planning, implementation, and evaluation. It guides individualized, goal-directed patient care.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (22, $x$Obtaining informed consent from research participants primarily upholds which ethical principle?$x$, $x$["Justice","Autonomy (respect for persons)","Non-maleficence","Beneficence"]$x$, 1, $x$Informed consent respects the participant's autonomy and right to self-determination by ensuring voluntary and informed participation. It is a core requirement for ethical research involving human subjects.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (23, $x$An advantage of a written nursing care plan is that it:$x$, $x$["Makes the medical diagnosis","Eliminates the need for patient assessment","Replaces the physician's orders","Promotes individualized and coordinated care"]$x$, 3, $x$A written care plan communicates individualized goals and interventions to all team members, promoting continuity and coordination of care. It does not replace assessment or the physician's orders.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (24, $x$A data-collection tool consisting of a set of written questions that respondents answer themselves is called a:$x$, $x$["Rating scale","Interview guide","Observation schedule","Questionnaire"]$x$, 3, $x$A questionnaire is a self-administered instrument containing written questions completed by the respondent. It is economical for large samples and can maintain the respondent's anonymity.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (25, $x$Evidence-based practice (EBP) integrates the best available research evidence with:$x$, $x$["Clinical expertise and patient values","The hospital budget alone","Tradition and intuition alone","Only the physician's personal preference"]$x$, 0, $x$EBP combines the best research evidence, the clinician's expertise, and the patient's values and preferences. This integrated approach improves the quality, safety, and outcomes of care.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (26, $x$The research process typically begins with which of the following steps?$x$, $x$["Analysis of data","Identifying and formulating the research problem","Collection of data","Writing the final report"]$x$, 1, $x$Research begins with identifying and clearly stating the research problem, which guides all subsequent steps. A well-defined problem shapes the objectives, design, and choice of methods.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (27, $x$The main purpose of conducting a review of literature is to:$x$, $x$["Increase the length of the report","Avoid acknowledging other researchers","Deliberately delay the study","Identify existing knowledge, gaps, and a theoretical basis for the study"]$x$, 3, $x$A literature review surveys existing studies to establish what is already known, identify gaps, and provide a conceptual or theoretical foundation. It prevents duplication and helps refine the research problem.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (28, $x$A research design that examines the relationship between two or more variables without manipulating them is called a:$x$, $x$["Historical design","Correlational design","Case-control design","Experimental design"]$x$, 1, $x$A correlational design measures variables as they naturally occur and assesses the strength and direction of their relationship. It does not involve manipulation of an independent variable.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (29, $x$In a true experimental design, the variable that the researcher deliberately manipulates is the:$x$, $x$["Dependent variable","Demographic variable","Extraneous variable","Independent variable"]$x$, 3, $x$In experimental research the independent variable is the intervention or treatment that the researcher manipulates. Its effect is measured on the dependent (outcome) variable, along with randomization and control.$x$, $x$Nursing Foundations$x$, $x$hard$x$)
) as v(pos, question, options, ci, exp, topic, diff);

-- 33-medsurg-cardiac.txt — 30 questions
with b as (
  insert into tests (title, topic, difficulty, duration_minutes)
  values ($x$w3-medsurg-d — ingested draft, verify before trusting$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, 'medium', 60)
  returning id
