insert into questions (test_id, position, question, options, correct_index, explanation, topic, difficulty)
select b.id, v.pos::int, v.question, v.options::jsonb, v.ci::int, v.exp, v.topic, v.diff
from b, (values
  (0, $x$Which ECG finding is characteristic of atrial fibrillation?$x$, $x$["Absent P waves with an irregularly irregular ventricular rhythm","Regular sawtooth flutter waves at a constant atrial rate","Wide, bizarre QRS complexes at a rapid regular rate","A progressively lengthening PR interval before a dropped beat"]$x$, 0, $x$Atrial fibrillation produces disorganized atrial activity, so discrete P waves are absent and are replaced by fibrillatory waves. Conduction to the ventricles is erratic, producing the classic irregularly irregular rhythm.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (1, $x$The classic regular "sawtooth" pattern of atrial waves on an ECG is seen in:$x$, $x$["First-degree AV block","Atrial fibrillation","Atrial flutter","Ventricular tachycardia"]$x$, 2, $x$Atrial flutter generates regular sawtooth-shaped flutter (F) waves, usually best seen in the inferior leads. The atrial rate is typically about 250 to 350 per minute with a regular ventricular response.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (2, $x$The immediate treatment of pulseless ventricular fibrillation is:$x$, $x$["Immediate defibrillation","Intravenous adenosine","Vagal maneuvers","Synchronized cardioversion"]$x$, 0, $x$Pulseless ventricular fibrillation is a lethal rhythm requiring immediate defibrillation to restore an organized rhythm. Early unsynchronized shock combined with CPR gives the best chance of survival.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (3, $x$Which statement correctly distinguishes synchronized cardioversion from defibrillation?$x$, $x$["Defibrillation is the treatment of choice for stable atrial fibrillation with a pulse","Defibrillation delivers the shock precisely timed to the R wave","Cardioversion delivers the shock synchronized to the R wave of the QRS complex","Cardioversion always uses a higher energy level than defibrillation"]$x$, 2, $x$Cardioversion delivers a lower-energy shock synchronized to the R wave to avoid the vulnerable T-wave period and prevent inducing ventricular fibrillation. Defibrillation is unsynchronized and used for pulseless VF or VT.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (4, $x$In third-degree (complete) heart block, the ECG shows:$x$, $x$["Progressive PR lengthening until a beat is dropped","A constantly prolonged PR interval with every beat conducted","Complete dissociation between the P waves and QRS complexes","Absent P waves with an irregularly irregular rhythm"]$x$, 2, $x$In complete heart block the atria and ventricles beat independently, so the P waves and QRS complexes have no fixed relationship. An escape pacemaker maintains the ventricular rhythm, which is often slow.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (5, $x$First-degree atrioventricular block is defined by:$x$, $x$["An irregularly irregular ventricular rhythm","Randomly dropped QRS complexes","A PR interval greater than 0.20 seconds with every impulse conducted","A widened QRS complex greater than 0.12 seconds"]$x$, 2, $x$First-degree AV block reflects delayed conduction through the AV node, prolonging the PR interval beyond 0.20 seconds. Every impulse is still conducted to the ventricles, so no beats are dropped.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (6, $x$Progressive lengthening of the PR interval until a QRS complex is dropped is characteristic of:$x$, $x$["Mobitz type I (Wenckebach) second-degree block","Mobitz type II second-degree block","Third-degree heart block","First-degree heart block"]$x$, 0, $x$Mobitz type I (Wenckebach) block shows progressive PR-interval prolongation until one P wave fails to conduct and a QRS is dropped. The cycle then repeats, and the rhythm is usually benign.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (7, $x$The ECG in ventricular tachycardia typically shows:$x$, $x$["Narrow QRS complexes at a normal rate","A flat isoelectric line","Regular sawtooth flutter waves","Three or more consecutive wide QRS complexes at a rapid rate"]$x$, 3, $x$Ventricular tachycardia is defined as three or more consecutive PVCs, producing wide, bizarre QRS complexes at a rapid rate. It may be life threatening and can deteriorate into ventricular fibrillation.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (8, $x$Asystole is best described on the ECG monitor as:$x$, $x$["A rapid wide-complex tachycardia","A regular sawtooth baseline","A flat line reflecting absence of ventricular electrical activity","Chaotic irregular deflections without organized complexes"]$x$, 2, $x$Asystole represents the total absence of ventricular electrical activity, seen as a nearly flat line on the monitor. It is treated with CPR and epinephrine rather than defibrillation.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (9, $x$A premature ventricular contraction (PVC) appears on the ECG as:$x$, $x$["A wide, bizarre QRS complex occurring earlier than expected without a preceding P wave","A narrow QRS complex preceded by a normal P wave","A regular sawtooth flutter wave","A prolonged flat isoelectric segment"]$x$, 0, $x$A PVC arises from an ectopic ventricular focus, producing a wide, bizarre QRS that comes early and is not preceded by a P wave. It is typically followed by a compensatory pause.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (10, $x$Intermittent claudication, the hallmark symptom of peripheral arterial disease, is:$x$, $x$["Reproducible muscle pain in the legs brought on by exercise and relieved by rest","Calf swelling with warmth, redness, and tenderness","Leg pain occurring at rest and relieved by leg dependency","Numbness of the feet occurring only during the night"]$x$, 0, $x$Intermittent claudication is ischemic muscle pain triggered when exercise increases oxygen demand that narrowed arteries cannot meet. Rest lowers the demand and relieves the pain, distinguishing it from venous disease.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (11, $x$To promote arterial perfusion in a patient with peripheral arterial disease, the nurse should position the legs:$x$, $x$["Elevated on two pillows at all times","Flat with the knees continuously flexed","In a slightly dependent (lowered) position","Elevated well above the level of the heart"]$x$, 2, $x$In arterial insufficiency, a dependent position uses gravity to enhance blood flow into the ischemic legs. Elevating the limbs would further reduce arterial perfusion and worsen ischemic pain.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (12, $x$Which finding most strongly indicates arterial rather than venous insufficiency?$x$, $x$["Warm, edematous lower legs","A cool, pale extremity with diminished or absent pedal pulses","Aching pain that is relieved by elevating the legs","Brownish hyperpigmentation around the medial ankle"]$x$, 1, $x$Arterial insufficiency causes cool, pale extremities with weak or absent pulses because of reduced inflow. Venous disease instead produces warm, edematous, hyperpigmented limbs with intact pulses.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (13, $x$A classic physical finding of an abdominal aortic aneurysm is:$x$, $x$["A pulsatile mass palpable in the abdomen","Marked jaundice of the sclera","Rebound tenderness in the right lower quadrant","Absent bowel sounds throughout the abdomen"]$x$, 0, $x$An abdominal aortic aneurysm classically presents as a pulsatile mass palpable near the umbilicus. Many are asymptomatic and are found incidentally during examination or imaging.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (14, $x$The nurse should suspect rupture of an abdominal aortic aneurysm when the patient develops:$x$, $x$["Sudden severe back or abdominal pain with hypotension and tachycardia","Bradycardia with a rising blood pressure","Localized tenderness of the calf muscle","Gradual onset of constipation and bloating"]$x$, 0, $x$Rupture of an aortic aneurysm produces sudden severe back or abdominal pain with signs of hemorrhagic shock such as hypotension and tachycardia. It is a surgical emergency requiring immediate intervention.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (15, $x$A sudden "tearing" or "ripping" chest pain radiating to the back is most characteristic of:$x$, $x$["Acute pericarditis","Gastroesophageal reflux disease","Aortic dissection","Stable angina pectoris"]$x$, 2, $x$Aortic dissection classically causes an abrupt, severe tearing or ripping pain that radiates to the back as blood splits the layers of the arterial wall. Rapid blood pressure control and imaging are essential.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (16, $x$Varicose veins develop primarily as a result of:$x$, $x$["Incompetent venous valves leading to venous stasis and dilation","Inflammation and thrombosis of small and medium arteries","Atherosclerotic narrowing of the arteries","Vasospasm of the digital arterioles"]$x$, 0, $x$Varicose veins result from incompetent valves that permit retrograde flow and venous pooling, distending and tortuously enlarging the superficial veins. Prolonged standing and raised venous pressure aggravate the condition.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (17, $x$Which bedside test is used to assess valvular competence of the veins in a patient with varicose veins?$x$, $x$["Trendelenburg test","Phalen maneuver","Allen test","Homan sign"]$x$, 0, $x$The Trendelenburg test evaluates competence of the venous valves by observing the pattern of vein refilling after leg elevation and tourniquet application. Rapid filling from above indicates valvular incompetence.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (18, $x$Raynaud phenomenon is characterized by:$x$, $x$["Continuous painless cyanosis of both lower limbs","Persistent warmth and redness of the hands and feet","Painless ulceration of the toes with absent pulses","Episodic vasospasm producing sequential white, blue, and red color changes of the digits"]$x$, 3, $x$Raynaud phenomenon is episodic arteriolar vasospasm, usually triggered by cold or stress, producing sequential pallor, cyanosis, and then rubor of the digits. The attacks are typically reversible with warming.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (19, $x$The most important self-care instruction for a patient with Raynaud phenomenon is to:$x$, $x$["Apply ice packs to the hands during an attack","Restrict daily fluid intake","Avoid cold exposure and stop smoking","Keep the hands immersed in cold water"]$x$, 2, $x$Avoiding cold exposure and eliminating tobacco, which is a potent vasoconstrictor, reduce the frequency and severity of Raynaud attacks. Keeping the hands and whole body warm is the cornerstone of management.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (20, $x$The single most important intervention in managing Buerger disease (thromboangiitis obliterans) is:$x$, $x$["Complete cessation of all tobacco use","Regular use of vasoconstrictor drugs","Lifelong anticoagulation therapy","A strict low-sodium diet"]$x$, 0, $x$Buerger disease is strongly linked to tobacco, and continued use drives progression toward ischemia and gangrene. Complete and permanent cessation of all tobacco is the only intervention that halts the disease.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (21, $x$Buerger disease characteristically affects:$x$, $x$["Large arteries of elderly postmenopausal women","The pulmonary arterial circulation","The coronary arteries exclusively","Small and medium arteries and veins of the extremities in young male smokers"]$x$, 3, $x$Thromboangiitis obliterans typically affects the small and medium arteries and veins of the extremities in young male smokers. Inflammatory thrombi occlude the vessels, causing ischemia and pain in the digits.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (22, $x$Which peripheral manifestation is characteristically associated with infective endocarditis?$x$, $x$["A butterfly (malar) facial rash","Heberden nodes over the finger joints","Osler nodes, Janeway lesions, and splinter hemorrhages","Xanthelasma around the eyelids"]$x$, 2, $x$Infective endocarditis produces peripheral signs such as painful Osler nodes, painless Janeway lesions, and splinter hemorrhages from septic emboli and immune complexes. Roth spots may also appear in the retina.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (23, $x$The characteristic lesion of infective endocarditis is:$x$, $x$["A fatty atheromatous plaque in the coronary arteries","A large accumulating pericardial effusion","Fibrous thickening and calcification of the pericardium","Vegetations of microorganisms and fibrin on the heart valves"]$x$, 3, $x$The hallmark of infective endocarditis is vegetations composed of microorganisms, platelets, and fibrin on the heart valves. Fragments may embolize elsewhere, and valve destruction can cause regurgitation.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (24, $x$Rheumatic heart disease in adults most commonly affects which cardiac valve?$x$, $x$["Aortic valve alone","Tricuspid valve","Pulmonic valve","Mitral valve"]$x$, 3, $x$Rheumatic heart disease most often damages the mitral valve, followed by the aortic valve. Chronic scarring produces stenosis or regurgitation years after the initial episode of rheumatic fever.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (25, $x$Rheumatic fever, which precedes rheumatic heart disease, follows infection with:$x$, $x$["Klebsiella pneumoniae","Staphylococcus aureus","Escherichia coli","Group A beta-hemolytic streptococcus"]$x$, 3, $x$Rheumatic fever is an immune reaction that follows pharyngitis caused by group A beta-hemolytic streptococcus. Prompt antibiotic treatment of streptococcal throat infection prevents its development.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (26, $x$The most common form of cardiomyopathy, marked by ventricular dilation and impaired systolic contraction, is:$x$, $x$["Arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy","Dilated cardiomyopathy","Restrictive cardiomyopathy","Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy"]$x$, 1, $x$Dilated cardiomyopathy is the most common type and features ventricular dilation with poor systolic function, leading to heart failure. It may be idiopathic or caused by alcohol, infection, or ischemia.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (27, $x$Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is an important cause of sudden cardiac death in:$x$, $x$["Neonates during the first week of life","Pregnant women in the third trimester","Elderly patients with long-standing hypertension","Apparently healthy young athletes"]$x$, 3, $x$Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy involves asymmetric myocardial thickening and is a leading cause of sudden cardiac death in young athletes. It can cause outflow obstruction and lethal arrhythmias during exertion.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (28, $x$After a cardiac catheterization performed through the femoral artery, the priority nursing assessment is:$x$, $x$["Pupillary size and reaction to light","The patient's level of orientation","Bowel sounds in all four quadrants","Peripheral pulses, color, and temperature of the affected extremity"]$x$, 3, $x$After femoral catheterization, assessing distal pulses, color, and temperature detects arterial occlusion or bleeding early. Neurovascular compromise of the affected limb is the priority complication to monitor.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (29, $x$Following a femoral-approach cardiac catheterization, the nurse should:$x$, $x$["Have the patient flex the hip and knee frequently","Encourage immediate ambulation to prevent clot formation","Withhold all oral fluids for the next 24 hours","Keep the affected leg straight and maintain bed rest as ordered"]$x$, 3, $x$Keeping the affected leg straight and maintaining bed rest reduce the risk of bleeding and hematoma at the femoral puncture site. The nurse also monitors the site and distal circulation frequently.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$)
) as v(pos, question, options, ci, exp, topic, diff);

-- 34-medsurg-neuro-ent.txt — 30 questions
with b as (
  insert into tests (title, topic, difficulty, duration_minutes)
  values ($x$w3-medsurg-e — ingested draft, verify before trusting$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, 'medium', 60)
  returning id
)
insert into questions (test_id, position, question, options, correct_index, explanation, topic, difficulty)
select b.id, v.pos::int, v.question, v.options::jsonb, v.ci::int, v.exp, v.topic, v.diff
from b, (values
  (0, $x$A patient experiences a prolonged generalized tonic-clonic seizure lasting more than 5 minutes without regaining consciousness. What is the first-line pharmacological management for this status epilepticus?$x$, $x$["Intravenous mannitol","Intravenous lorazepam","Intramuscular vitamin B12","Oral carbamazepine"]$x$, 1, $x$Intravenous benzodiazepines such as lorazepam are the first-line drugs to abort status epilepticus. They act rapidly to terminate seizure activity, after which longer-acting agents like phenytoin are added.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (1, $x$Which type of seizure is characterized by a brief loss of awareness with staring and eyelid fluttering, most common in children and formerly called petit mal?$x$, $x$["Tonic-clonic seizure","Myoclonic seizure","Absence seizure","Atonic seizure"]$x$, 2, $x$Absence seizures cause a brief lapse of consciousness lasting seconds with staring and no postictal confusion. They are typical of childhood and were previously termed petit mal seizures.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (2, $x$Bell palsy involves paralysis of which cranial nerve?$x$, $x$["Trigeminal nerve","Vagus nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Facial nerve"]$x$, 3, $x$Bell palsy is an acute idiopathic paralysis of the seventh cranial (facial) nerve. It causes unilateral facial weakness affecting both upper and lower face on the same side.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (3, $x$A key nursing priority for a patient with Bell palsy is protection of which structure due to incomplete eyelid closure?$x$, $x$["The nasal mucosa","The cornea","The tongue","The tympanic membrane"]$x$, 1, $x$Because the affected eye cannot close fully, the cornea is at risk of drying and ulceration. Artificial tears, lubricant ointment, and an eye patch protect the exposed cornea.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (4, $x$Trigeminal neuralgia is characterized by which classic clinical feature?$x$, $x$["Gradual progressive hearing loss","Continuous dull bilateral headache","Sudden brief severe stabbing facial pain triggered by touch","Painless drooping of the eyelid"]$x$, 2, $x$Trigeminal neuralgia produces paroxysms of sudden, severe, electric shock-like or stabbing pain along the trigeminal nerve distribution. Pain is often triggered by touch, chewing, or a cold breeze on the face.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (5, $x$Which drug is considered the first-line medical treatment for trigeminal neuralgia?$x$, $x$["Prednisolone","Carbamazepine","Aspirin","Morphine"]$x$, 1, $x$Carbamazepine is the drug of choice for trigeminal neuralgia and relieves pain in most patients. It stabilizes neuronal membranes and reduces the paroxysmal discharges responsible for the pain.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (6, $x$A patient with diabetic peripheral neuropathy most commonly reports which distribution of symptoms?$x$, $x$["Loss of vision in one eye","Unilateral facial numbness","Symmetrical stocking-and-glove numbness and tingling","Sudden hemiplegia"]$x$, 2, $x$Diabetic peripheral neuropathy typically produces a symmetrical stocking-and-glove pattern affecting the distal feet before the hands. Patients report numbness, tingling, burning pain, and loss of protective sensation.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (7, $x$Which is the most common primary malignant brain tumour in adults?$x$, $x$["Pituitary adenoma","Glioblastoma multiforme","Acoustic neuroma","Meningioma"]$x$, 1, $x$Glioblastoma multiforme is the most common and most aggressive primary malignant brain tumour in adults. It arises from astrocytes and carries a poor prognosis despite treatment.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (8, $x$The classic early morning headache that worsens with coughing or straining in a brain tumour patient is caused primarily by which mechanism?$x$, $x$["Decreased cerebral blood flow","Meningeal infection","Hypoglycaemia","Raised intracranial pressure"]$x$, 3, $x$Brain tumours increase intracranial pressure, producing headache that is worse in the morning and aggravated by coughing, straining, or bending. Associated features include projectile vomiting and papilloedema.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (9, $x$Hydrocephalus is best defined as which of the following?$x$, $x$["Inflammation of the meninges","Degeneration of motor neurons","Bleeding into the subarachnoid space","Excess accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid within the ventricles"]$x$, 3, $x$Hydrocephalus is an abnormal accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid within the cerebral ventricles. It results from overproduction, obstructed flow, or impaired absorption of CSF and raises intracranial pressure.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (10, $x$A ventriculoperitoneal shunt drains cerebrospinal fluid from the ventricles into which body cavity?$x$, $x$["The peritoneal cavity","The pericardial sac","The urinary bladder","The pleural cavity"]$x$, 0, $x$A ventriculoperitoneal shunt diverts CSF from the cerebral ventricles to the peritoneal cavity where it is absorbed. This relieves raised intracranial pressure caused by hydrocephalus.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (11, $x$A child with a ventriculoperitoneal shunt develops fever, vomiting, irritability, and a bulging fontanelle. The nurse should first suspect which complication?$x$, $x$["Improved CSF absorption","Shunt blockage or infection","Normal shunt function","Dehydration only"]$x$, 1, $x$Signs of raised intracranial pressure with fever suggest shunt obstruction or infection. Prompt recognition and referral are essential because untreated shunt malfunction can be rapidly fatal.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (12, $x$Prolapse of an intervertebral disc most commonly occurs at which region of the spine?$x$, $x$["Sacral spine","Thoracic spine T4-T5","Cervical spine C1-C2","Lumbar spine L4-L5 and L5-S1"]$x$, 3, $x$The lumbar region, especially the L4-L5 and L5-S1 levels, bears the greatest mechanical load and is the most common site of disc prolapse. Herniation here compresses nerve roots causing low back pain and sciatica.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (13, $x$Sciatica typically produces pain radiating in which pattern?$x$, $x$["Into the fingertips of both hands","Across the shoulders and neck","From the lower back down the back of the leg to the foot","Around the chest wall"]$x$, 2, $x$Sciatica is pain along the course of the sciatic nerve, radiating from the lower back through the buttock and down the posterior thigh and leg. It usually results from compression of a lumbosacral nerve root.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (14, $x$Which bedside test reproduces sciatic nerve pain by lifting the extended leg and is used to assess lumbar disc herniation?$x$, $x$["Kernig sign","Brudzinski sign","Romberg test","Straight leg raise test"]$x$, 3, $x$The straight leg raise test stretches the sciatic nerve and reproduces radicular pain when a lumbar disc herniation compresses a nerve root. A positive test supports the diagnosis of lumbar radiculopathy.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (15, $x$Cervical myelopathy results from compression of which structure?$x$, $x$["The peripheral nerves of the arm","The facial nerve","The spinal cord in the cervical region","The brachial artery"]$x$, 2, $x$Cervical myelopathy is dysfunction caused by compression of the spinal cord in the neck, often from degenerative spondylosis. It produces gait disturbance, hand clumsiness, and upper motor neuron signs such as hyperreflexia.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (16, $x$Myopia (nearsightedness) is best corrected with which type of lens?$x$, $x$["Cylindrical lens","Prism lens","Concave (diverging) lens","Convex (converging) lens"]$x$, 2, $x$In myopia the image focuses in front of the retina, so a concave diverging lens is used to move the focal point back onto the retina. This allows clear distance vision.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (17, $x$Hypermetropia (farsightedness) occurs because light rays focus where relative to the retina?$x$, $x$["Behind the retina","At the optic disc","Directly on the retina","In front of the retina"]$x$, 0, $x$In hypermetropia the eyeball is relatively too short or refractive power too weak, so parallel rays focus behind the retina. A convex converging lens corrects this by bringing the focus forward onto the retina.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (18, $x$Astigmatism is caused by which structural abnormality of the eye?$x$, $x$["Increased intraocular pressure","An irregularly curved cornea","Clouding of the lens","A detached retina"]$x$, 1, $x$Astigmatism results from an unevenly curved cornea (or lens) that refracts light unequally in different meridians. This produces blurred or distorted vision that is corrected with cylindrical lenses.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (19, $x$A patient reports sudden onset of floaters, flashes of light, and a curtain-like shadow across the visual field. Which condition is most likely?$x$, $x$["Conjunctivitis","Refractive error","Retinal detachment","Stye"]$x$, 2, $x$Retinal detachment classically presents with floaters, light flashes, and a progressive curtain or shadow over the visual field. It is an ophthalmic emergency requiring prompt surgical repair to preserve vision.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (20, $x$Trachoma, a leading infectious cause of blindness, is caused by which organism?$x$, $x$["Candida albicans","Chlamydia trachomatis","Staphylococcus aureus","Herpes simplex virus"]$x$, 1, $x$Trachoma is a chronic keratoconjunctivitis caused by Chlamydia trachomatis. Repeated infection leads to conjunctival scarring, entropion, trichiasis, and eventually corneal blindness if untreated.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (21, $x$A patient presents with a red eye, mucopurulent discharge, and eyelids stuck together on waking, but with normal vision. Which condition is most likely?$x$, $x$["Acute glaucoma","Cataract","Retinal detachment","Bacterial conjunctivitis"]$x$, 3, $x$Bacterial conjunctivitis causes a red eye with purulent discharge and lids that are stuck together in the morning, while vision remains normal. It is highly contagious and managed with topical antibiotics and hygiene measures.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (22, $x$A corneal ulcer that stains green when fluorescein dye is applied indicates which of the following?$x$, $x$["A healthy intact cornea","A cataract","An epithelial defect with corneal ulceration","Normal tear film"]$x$, 2, $x$Fluorescein dye pools in areas where the corneal epithelium is lost, staining the ulcer green under blue light. This confirms an epithelial defect and helps assess the size of a corneal ulcer.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (23, $x$Strabismus (squint) is best described as which condition?$x$, $x$["Increased intraocular pressure","Misalignment of the visual axes of the two eyes","Clouding of the lens","Inflammation of the eyelid margin"]$x$, 1, $x$Strabismus is a misalignment of the eyes in which the visual axes are not directed at the same point simultaneously. If untreated in childhood it can lead to amblyopia (lazy eye) in the deviating eye.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (24, $x$Acute otitis media is an infection and inflammation of which part of the ear?$x$, $x$["The middle ear","The pinna","The external auditory canal","The inner ear cochlea"]$x$, 0, $x$Acute otitis media is an infection of the middle ear cavity, commonly following an upper respiratory tract infection via the Eustachian tube. It presents with ear pain, fever, and a bulging red tympanic membrane.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (25, $x$In the Rinne test, a patient with conductive hearing loss will demonstrate which finding?$x$, $x$["Complete absence of both conductions","Bone conduction better than air conduction","Equal air and bone conduction with no lateralization","Air conduction better than bone conduction"]$x$, 1, $x$In conductive hearing loss the Rinne test is negative, meaning bone conduction is heard longer or louder than air conduction. This occurs because the impaired middle ear cannot efficiently transmit air-conducted sound.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (26, $x$Otosclerosis causes hearing loss primarily by which mechanism?$x$, $x$["Blockage of the external canal with wax","Rupture of the tympanic membrane","Fixation of the stapes footplate in the oval window","Damage to the cochlear hair cells"]$x$, 2, $x$Otosclerosis is abnormal bony remodeling that fixes the stapes footplate to the oval window, preventing sound transmission to the inner ear. This produces a progressive conductive hearing loss, often treated by stapedectomy.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (27, $x$Sensorineural hearing loss results from damage to which structures?$x$, $x$["The external auditory canal","The ossicles of the middle ear","The cochlea or auditory nerve","The tympanic membrane"]$x$, 2, $x$Sensorineural hearing loss arises from damage to the cochlear hair cells or the auditory (eighth cranial) nerve pathway. Unlike conductive loss it is usually permanent and may be managed with hearing aids or cochlear implants.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (28, $x$The most common cause of anterior epistaxis (nosebleed) is bleeding from which site?$x$, $x$["The maxillary sinus","Little area (Kiesselbach plexus) on the anterior nasal septum","Sphenopalatine artery posteriorly","The frontal sinus"]$x$, 1, $x$Most anterior nosebleeds originate from Little area, the Kiesselbach plexus on the anterior nasal septum where several vessels anastomose. This site is easily traumatized and bleeding is usually controlled with pinching and pressure.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (29, $x$A child suddenly develops noisy breathing and unilateral foul-smelling nasal discharge. The nurse should suspect which cause?$x$, $x$["Deviated nasal septum","Chronic sinusitis","A nasal foreign body","Allergic rhinitis"]$x$, 2, $x$A unilateral, foul-smelling, and sometimes blood-stained nasal discharge in a child strongly suggests an impacted nasal foreign body. Prompt removal prevents complications such as infection or aspiration.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$)
) as v(pos, question, options, ci, exp, topic, diff);

-- 35-medsurg-gi-gu.txt — 30 questions
with b as (
  insert into tests (title, topic, difficulty, duration_minutes)
  values ($x$w3-medsurg-f — ingested draft, verify before trusting$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, 'medium', 60)
  returning id
)
insert into questions (test_id, position, question, options, correct_index, explanation, topic, difficulty)
select b.id, v.pos::int, v.question, v.options::jsonb, v.ci::int, v.exp, v.topic, v.diff
from b, (values
  (0, $x$Which of the following is the most characteristic symptom of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GERD)?$x$, $x$["Projectile vomiting","Steatorrhoea","Melaena","Heartburn (pyrosis)"]$x$, 3, $x$Heartburn, a retrosternal burning sensation, is the classic symptom of GERD caused by reflux of acidic gastric contents into the oesophagus. It is typically worse after meals and on lying flat, and may be accompanied by regurgitation.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (1, $x$Long-standing GERD can cause columnar metaplasia of the distal oesophageal epithelium, a premalignant condition known as:$x$, $x$["Mallory-Weiss tear","Plummer-Vinson syndrome","Barrett's oesophagus","Zenker's diverticulum"]$x$, 2, $x$Barrett's oesophagus is replacement of the normal squamous epithelium by columnar (intestinal-type) epithelium due to chronic acid injury. It is a premalignant change that increases the risk of oesophageal adenocarcinoma and warrants endoscopic surveillance.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (2, $x$The most common type of hiatus hernia is:$x$, $x$["Sliding (type I)","Type IV with additional organ herniation","Paraoesophageal (type II)","Mixed (type III)"]$x$, 0, $x$The sliding (type I) hiatus hernia accounts for roughly 90% of cases, in which the gastro-oesophageal junction and cardia slide up through the diaphragmatic hiatus. Paraoesophageal (rolling) hernias are less common but carry a higher risk of strangulation.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (3, $x$Maximal tenderness in acute appendicitis is classically located at McBurney's point, which lies:$x$, $x$["At the umbilicus","One-third of the way from the anterior superior iliac spine to the umbilicus","In the right hypochondrium","In the left iliac fossa"]$x$, 1, $x$McBurney's point lies one-third of the distance along a line drawn from the right anterior superior iliac spine to the umbilicus. Localised tenderness here reflects parietal peritoneal irritation over the inflamed appendix.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (4, $x$Which sign, in which palpation of the left lower quadrant elicits pain in the right lower quadrant, supports a diagnosis of acute appendicitis?$x$, $x$["Cullen's sign","Grey Turner's sign","Rovsing's sign","Murphy's sign"]$x$, 2, $x$Rovsing's sign is referred right iliac fossa pain produced by palpating the left lower quadrant, indicating peritoneal irritation from the inflamed appendix. Murphy's sign relates to cholecystitis, while Cullen's and Grey Turner's signs suggest retroperitoneal or intra-abdominal haemorrhage.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (5, $x$A hallmark clinical finding of generalised peritonitis is:$x$, $x$["Bounding femoral pulses","Painless abdominal distension","Board-like rigidity of the abdominal wall","High-pitched hyperactive bowel sounds"]$x$, 2, $x$Diffuse peritoneal inflammation produces involuntary guarding and board-like rigidity of the abdominal wall, with rebound tenderness and absent (silent) bowel sounds from paralytic ileus. It is a surgical emergency requiring prompt resuscitation and source control.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (6, $x$The most common type of abdominal wall hernia overall is:$x$, $x$["Inguinal hernia","Incisional hernia","Femoral hernia","Umbilical hernia"]$x$, 0, $x$Inguinal hernias are the most common abdominal wall hernias and occur far more frequently in males. They may be indirect (through the deep inguinal ring) or direct (through the posterior wall of the inguinal canal).$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (7, $x$A femoral hernia protrudes through the femoral canal and characteristically presents as a lump located:$x$, $x$["Above and medial to the pubic tubercle","In the epigastrium","Below and lateral to the pubic tubercle","At the umbilicus"]$x$, 2, $x$A femoral hernia emerges below and lateral to the pubic tubercle, whereas an inguinal hernia lies above and medial to it. Femoral hernias are commoner in women and carry a high risk of strangulation because of the narrow, rigid femoral canal.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (8, $x$Internal haemorrhoids that prolapse on defecation but reduce spontaneously are classified as:$x$, $x$["Third degree","Fourth degree","First degree","Second degree"]$x$, 3, $x$Second-degree internal haemorrhoids prolapse during defecation and then reduce on their own. First-degree haemorrhoids bleed without prolapse, third-degree require manual reduction, and fourth-degree are permanently prolapsed and irreducible.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (9, $x$The rule used to predict the course of an anal fistula tract based on the position of its external opening is:$x$, $x$["Virchow's law","Charcot's triad","Courvoisier's law","Goodsall's rule"]$x$, 3, $x$Goodsall's rule states that a fistula with an external opening anterior to the transverse anal line usually runs a straight radial course to the anal canal, while a posterior opening tends to follow a curved track opening in the posterior midline. It guides surgical exploration of the tract.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (10, $x$Which serum tumour marker is most commonly used to monitor recurrence in colorectal cancer?$x$, $x$["Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP)","Prostate-specific antigen (PSA)","Carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA)","CA-125"]$x$, 2, $x$CEA is used chiefly for postoperative surveillance and detection of recurrence in colorectal cancer, not for primary screening. A rising CEA level after curative resection suggests recurrent or metastatic disease.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (11, $x$The diffuse infiltrative form of gastric adenocarcinoma that produces a rigid, thickened "leather-bottle" stomach is termed:$x$, $x$["Menetrier's disease","Linitis plastica","Zollinger-Ellison syndrome","Krukenberg tumour"]$x$, 1, $x$Linitis plastica is a diffusely infiltrating gastric carcinoma (often with signet-ring cells) that thickens and stiffens the stomach wall, giving a leather-bottle appearance. It carries a poor prognosis because of extensive submucosal spread at presentation.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (12, $x$The most sensitive and specific serological test for coeliac disease is:$x$, $x$["Anti-smooth muscle antibody","Anti-mitochondrial antibody","Anti-tissue transglutaminase (tTG) IgA antibody","Anti-nuclear antibody"]$x$, 2, $x$IgA anti-tissue transglutaminase antibody is the first-line screening test for coeliac disease owing to its high sensitivity and specificity. Diagnosis is confirmed by duodenal biopsy showing villous atrophy, and total IgA should be checked to exclude IgA deficiency.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (13, $x$Which finding is most characteristic of fat malabsorption?$x$, $x$["Painless haematuria","Projectile bilious vomiting","Bulky, pale, foul-smelling, greasy stools (steatorrhoea)","Bright red blood per rectum"]$x$, 2, $x$Steatorrhoea, the passage of bulky, pale, greasy and offensive stools that are difficult to flush, is the hallmark of fat malabsorption. It may be accompanied by weight loss and deficiencies of fat-soluble vitamins A, D, E and K.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (14, $x$Which pair of hepatitis viruses is transmitted predominantly by the faecal-oral route?$x$, $x$["Hepatitis B and C","Hepatitis C and D","Hepatitis B and D","Hepatitis A and E"]$x$, 3, $x$Hepatitis A and E spread mainly by the faecal-oral route, often through contaminated food or water, and typically cause acute self-limiting illness. Hepatitis B, C and D are transmitted parenterally and can progress to chronic infection.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (15, $x$Hepatitis D (delta) virus can cause infection only in the presence of:$x$, $x$["Hepatitis A virus","Hepatitis B virus","Hepatitis C virus","Hepatitis E virus"]$x$, 1, $x$Hepatitis D is a defective virus that requires the hepatitis B surface antigen to assemble and replicate. It occurs only as a co-infection or superinfection with HBV, and vaccination against hepatitis B therefore also prevents hepatitis D.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (16, $x$Fulminant hepatic failure is defined as the development of hepatic encephalopathy within how long of the onset of symptoms in a patient without pre-existing liver disease?$x$, $x$["Within 6 months","Within 2 years","Within 8 weeks","Within 1 year"]$x$, 2, $x$Fulminant (acute) hepatic failure is classically defined as encephalopathy developing within about 8 weeks of the onset of symptoms in a previously healthy liver. It reflects massive hepatocyte necrosis, commonly from paracetamol toxicity or viral hepatitis, and carries a high mortality.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (17, $x$Which of the following is a direct consequence of portal hypertension?$x$, $x$["Oesophageal varices","Gallstones","Pyelonephritis","Acute pancreatitis"]$x$, 0, $x$Raised pressure in the portal venous system opens portosystemic collateral channels, producing oesophageal and gastric varices, caput medusae and splenomegaly. Rupture of varices causes life-threatening upper gastrointestinal haemorrhage.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (18, $x$In hepatic encephalopathy, obvious asterixis with lethargy, apathy and disorientation to time, while the patient remains arousable, corresponds to which West Haven grade?$x$, $x$["Grade III","Grade IV","Grade II","Grade I"]$x$, 2, $x$West Haven grade II features lethargy or apathy, disorientation to time, obvious asterixis and personality change, with the patient still arousable. Grade III involves marked confusion and somnolence with response to stimuli, and grade IV denotes coma.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (19, $x$The most common causative organism of uncomplicated urinary tract infection is:$x$, $x$["Staphylococcus aureus","Escherichia coli","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Klebsiella pneumoniae"]$x$, 1, $x$Escherichia coli, a Gram-negative enteric bacterium, causes the great majority of uncomplicated urinary tract infections through ascending colonisation from the perineum. Typical symptoms include dysuria, frequency and urgency.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (20, $x$Acute pyelonephritis is best distinguished from lower urinary tract infection (cystitis) by the presence of:$x$, $x$["Absence of pyuria","Painless haematuria","Suprapubic pain only","Fever, chills and costovertebral angle (flank) tenderness"]$x$, 3, $x$Pyelonephritis is infection of the renal pelvis and parenchyma and typically presents with high fever, rigors, flank pain and costovertebral angle tenderness alongside lower urinary symptoms. Systemic features distinguish it from simple cystitis, which is usually confined to dysuria and frequency.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (21, $x$Adult post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis classically presents 1-3 weeks after infection with:$x$, $x$["Massive proteinuria and normal urine colour","Isolated sterile pyuria","Haematuria (smoky urine), hypertension and periorbital oedema","Glycosuria and polyuria"]$x$, 2, $x$Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis follows a group A streptococcal throat or skin infection and produces a nephritic picture of haematuria (smoky, cola-coloured urine), hypertension, oliguria and periorbital oedema. It is immune-complex mediated, and complement C3 is typically low.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (22, $x$Prostate cancer most commonly arises in which zone of the prostate and is monitored with which marker?$x$, $x$["Transition zone; CEA","Periurethral zone; CA-125","Peripheral zone; prostate-specific antigen (PSA)","Central zone; AFP"]$x$, 2, $x$Most prostate adenocarcinomas arise in the peripheral zone, which is why they are often palpable as a hard nodule on digital rectal examination. Serum PSA is used for detection and monitoring, whereas benign prostatic hyperplasia typically involves the transition zone.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (23, $x$A 15-year-old boy presents with sudden severe testicular pain, a high-riding testis and an absent cremasteric reflex. The most appropriate management is:$x$, $x$["Scrotal elevation and observation for 48 hours","Warm compresses and analgesia only","Oral antibiotics and discharge","Immediate surgical exploration"]$x$, 3, $x$These features are classic for testicular torsion, a surgical emergency in which the twisted spermatic cord cuts off blood supply to the testis. Immediate exploration and detorsion within about 6 hours is essential to salvage the testis, and the contralateral side is usually fixed as well.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (24, $x$The most common presenting feature of bladder carcinoma is:$x$, $x$["Severe flank colic","Painless gross (visible) haematuria","Nocturnal enuresis","Painful dysuria with fever"]$x$, 1, $x$Painless visible (gross) haematuria is the classic and most common presentation of bladder cancer, most of which are transitional cell (urothelial) carcinomas. Any adult with painless haematuria requires urological evaluation including cystoscopy.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (25, $x$The most common causative organisms of cellulitis are:$x$, $x$["Escherichia coli and Klebsiella","Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Candida albicans and Aspergillus","Streptococcus pyogenes and Staphylococcus aureus"]$x$, 3, $x$Cellulitis is an acute spreading infection of the dermis and subcutaneous tissue usually caused by beta-haemolytic streptococci (Streptococcus pyogenes) and Staphylococcus aureus. It presents with warm, tender, poorly demarcated erythema and is treated with systemic antibiotics.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (26, $x$Herpes zoster (shingles) is caused by:$x$, $x$["Human papillomavirus","Measles virus","Herpes simplex virus type 2","Reactivation of the varicella-zoster virus"]$x$, 3, $x$Herpes zoster results from reactivation of latent varicella-zoster virus residing in the dorsal root ganglia after a previous chickenpox infection. It produces a painful vesicular rash in a unilateral dermatomal distribution and may be followed by post-herpetic neuralgia.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (27, $x$Scabies is caused by infestation with:$x$, $x$["Demodex folliculorum","Sarcoptes scabiei","Trichophyton rubrum","Pediculus humanus"]$x$, 1, $x$Scabies is caused by the mite Sarcoptes scabiei var. hominis, which burrows into the epidermis and provokes intense itching that is characteristically worse at night. Typical sites include the finger webs, wrists and genitalia, and permethrin is a first-line treatment.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (28, $x$Tinea corporis (ringworm) of the skin is caused by:$x$, $x$["Streptococcus pyogenes","Sarcoptes scabiei","Herpes simplex virus","Dermatophyte fungi such as Trichophyton"]$x$, 3, $x$Ringworm and other tinea infections are caused by dermatophyte fungi of the genera Trichophyton, Microsporum and Epidermophyton. They produce annular, scaly, erythematous plaques with central clearing and are treated with topical or systemic antifungals.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (29, $x$The mnemonic used to identify warning features of malignant melanoma in a pigmented skin lesion is:$x$, $x$["Asymmetry, Border irregularity, Colour variation, Diameter over 6 mm, Evolution (ABCDE)","CURB-65","SOCRATES","FAST (Face, Arm, Speech, Time)"]$x$, 0, $x$The ABCDE criteria highlight suspicious features of melanoma: Asymmetry, irregular Border, Colour variation, Diameter greater than 6 mm, and Evolution or change over time. Any lesion showing these features, or new itching, bleeding or ulceration, warrants urgent dermatological assessment and biopsy.$x$, $x$Medical-Surgical Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$)
) as v(pos, question, options, ci, exp, topic, diff);

-- 36-mental-disorders-2.txt — 30 questions
with b as (
  insert into tests (title, topic, difficulty, duration_minutes)
  values ($x$w3-mental-b — ingested draft, verify before trusting$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, 'medium', 60)
  returning id
)
insert into questions (test_id, position, question, options, correct_index, explanation, topic, difficulty)
select b.id, v.pos::int, v.question, v.options::jsonb, v.ci::int, v.exp, v.topic, v.diff
from b, (values
  (0, $x$Russell's sign, seen in patients with long-standing bulimia nervosa, refers to:$x$, $x$["Erosion of dental enamel","Callus or scarring over the knuckles from self-induced vomiting","Fine downy lanugo hair over the body","Bilateral parotid gland enlargement"]$x$, 1, $x$Russell's sign is a callus or abrasion on the dorsum of the hand and knuckles caused by repeated contact with the teeth during self-induced vomiting. It is a classic physical marker of chronic bulimia nervosa.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (1, $x$The most dangerous electrolyte disturbance resulting from repeated purging in bulimia nervosa is:$x$, $x$["Hypernatraemia","Hypokalaemia","Hyperchloraemia","Hypercalcaemia"]$x$, 1, $x$Repeated vomiting and laxative misuse cause loss of potassium, producing hypokalaemia that can precipitate cardiac arrhythmias and sudden death. Monitoring serum potassium is essential in purging-type eating disorders.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (2, $x$Binge-eating disorder is differentiated from bulimia nervosa mainly by the:$x$, $x$["Absence of regular inappropriate compensatory behaviour","Marked concern about body shape and weight","Presence of recurrent binge-eating episodes","Feeling of loss of control while eating"]$x$, 0, $x$Both conditions involve recurrent binges with loss of control, but binge-eating disorder lacks the regular compensatory behaviours (vomiting, laxatives, fasting, exercise) seen in bulimia. Patients are therefore often overweight or obese.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (3, $x$Refeeding syndrome, a risk when nutrition is restarted in a severely malnourished eating-disorder patient, is characterised chiefly by:$x$, $x$["Hyperkalaemia and hypernatraemia","Hyperphosphataemia and hyperglycaemia","Hypophosphataemia with fluid and electrolyte shifts","Hypercalcaemia and metabolic alkalosis"]$x$, 2, $x$When feeding resumes, an insulin surge drives phosphate, potassium and magnesium into cells, causing dangerous hypophosphataemia and fluid shifts. This can lead to cardiac failure, arrhythmia and death, so refeeding must begin slowly with monitoring.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (4, $x$Insomnia is best defined as:$x$, $x$["Difficulty initiating or maintaining sleep, or non-restorative sleep","Excessive daytime sleepiness despite adequate night sleep","Recurrent irresistible attacks of sleep during the day","Abnormal behaviour or events occurring during sleep"]$x$, 0, $x$Insomnia is a subjective complaint of difficulty falling asleep, staying asleep, early-morning waking, or poor-quality sleep with daytime impairment. It is the most common sleep disorder encountered in clinical practice.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (5, $x$In narcolepsy, the sudden bilateral loss of muscle tone triggered by strong emotion is termed:$x$, $x$["Cataplexy","Catatonia","Cataphasia","Catalepsy"]$x$, 0, $x$Cataplexy is a brief, sudden loss of voluntary muscle tone provoked by emotions such as laughter or anger, and is a hallmark of narcolepsy. It occurs with preserved consciousness, unlike a seizure.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (6, $x$Narcolepsy with cataplexy is most closely linked to a deficiency of which hypothalamic neuropeptide?$x$, $x$["Orexin (hypocretin)","Gamma-aminobutyric acid","Melatonin","Serotonin"]$x$, 0, $x$Narcolepsy type 1 results from loss of hypothalamic neurons producing orexin (hypocretin), which normally stabilises wakefulness and suppresses REM sleep. Low CSF orexin levels support the diagnosis.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (7, $x$The treatment of choice for moderate-to-severe obstructive sleep apnoea is:$x$, $x$["Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors","Long-term benzodiazepine therapy","Stimulant medication at bedtime","Continuous positive airway pressure (CPAP)"]$x$, 3, $x$CPAP delivers positive pressure that splints the upper airway open, preventing the repetitive collapse and apnoeas of obstructive sleep apnoea. Sedatives are avoided as they worsen airway collapse and respiratory depression.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (8, $x$Somnambulism (sleepwalking) characteristically arises during:$x$, $x$["Rapid eye movement (REM) sleep","Slow-wave (deep NREM) sleep","Stage 2 NREM sleep","Sleep-onset stage 1"]$x$, 1, $x$Sleepwalking is a NREM parasomnia occurring during slow-wave sleep, usually in the first third of the night. The person has little or no recall of the episode, and it is common in children.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (9, $x$Gender dysphoria is characterised by:$x$, $x$["Recurrent urges to expose one's genitals to strangers","Sexual arousal derived from inanimate objects","Marked incongruence between one's experienced gender and assigned sex, causing distress","Sexual attraction directed towards the same gender"]$x$, 2, $x$Gender dysphoria refers to clinically significant distress arising from a mismatch between an individual's experienced or expressed gender and the sex assigned at birth. It is distinct from sexual orientation.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (10, $x$Vaginismus is best described as:$x$, $x$["Involuntary spasm of the perivaginal muscles preventing penetration","Persistent lack of sexual desire or interest","Inability to achieve orgasm despite adequate stimulation","Pain experienced only after intercourse"]$x$, 0, $x$Vaginismus involves recurrent involuntary contraction of the outer vaginal and perineal muscles, making penetration painful or impossible. It is a sexual pain and penetration disorder often with a psychological component.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (11, $x$Hypochondriasis is characterised by:$x$, $x$["Multiple recurrent physical complaints across several systems","Persistent preoccupation with the fear of having a serious illness","Preoccupation with an imagined defect in physical appearance","Loss of a physical function without organic basis"]$x$, 1, $x$Hypochondriasis (illness anxiety) is a persistent preoccupation with, and fear of, having one or more serious diseases, based on misinterpretation of normal bodily sensations. Reassurance gives only brief relief.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (12, $x$Somatisation disorder (Briquet's syndrome) is best characterised by:$x$, $x$["Multiple, recurrent, changing physical complaints involving several organ systems","A single medically unexplained neurological deficit","Preoccupation with a perceived bodily defect","Fixed conviction of suffering from one specific disease"]$x$, 0, $x$Somatisation disorder involves numerous recurring, often changing, physical symptoms across multiple organ systems for which no adequate physical cause is found. It usually begins before age 30 and follows a chronic course.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (13, $x$Body dysmorphic disorder is defined by:$x$, $x$["An intense fear of gaining weight","Preoccupation with an imagined or slight defect in physical appearance","Fixed false belief of having a serious disease","Multiple unexplained somatic complaints"]$x$, 1, $x$In body dysmorphic disorder the person is preoccupied with a perceived flaw in appearance that is unnoticeable or slight to others, leading to repetitive checking or camouflaging. It causes marked distress and impairment.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (14, $x$Obsessions in obsessive-compulsive disorder are:$x$, $x$["Repetitive purposeful behaviours performed to reduce anxiety","False sensory perceptions without an external stimulus","Recurrent, intrusive, unwanted thoughts, images or impulses","Fixed false beliefs held despite contrary evidence"]$x$, 2, $x$Obsessions are recurrent, persistent, intrusive and unwanted thoughts, images or urges that cause marked anxiety and are recognised by the patient as their own. Compulsions are the repetitive acts performed to neutralise them.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (15, $x$The most effective specific psychological treatment for obsessive-compulsive disorder is:$x$, $x$["Systematic desensitisation","Free association","Exposure and response prevention","Aversion therapy"]$x$, 2, $x$Exposure and response prevention (ERP), a form of behaviour therapy, exposes the patient to anxiety-provoking triggers while preventing the compulsive response. Combined with SSRIs it is first-line treatment for OCD.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (16, $x$Trichotillomania, classified among obsessive-compulsive and related disorders, refers to:$x$, $x$["Compulsive skin-picking causing lesions","Repetitive hand-washing rituals","Compulsive hoarding of worthless objects","Recurrent pulling out of one's own hair causing hair loss"]$x$, 3, $x$Trichotillomania is characterised by recurrent, irresistible pulling out of one's hair, resulting in noticeable hair loss, with repeated attempts to stop. It is grouped with OCD-related disorders in modern classifications.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (17, $x$Adjustment disorder is best described as:$x$, $x$["A lifelong maladaptive pattern of behaviour","Maladaptive emotional or behavioural symptoms arising within three months of an identifiable stressor","A psychotic reaction lasting more than six months","Emotional symptoms arising without any identifiable stressor"]$x$, 1, $x$Adjustment disorder involves emotional or behavioural symptoms developing within three months of an identifiable psychosocial stressor and typically resolving within six months of its cessation. The reaction is out of proportion to the stressor.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (18, $x$A characteristic feature of acute and transient psychotic disorder is:$x$, $x$["Persistent symptoms lasting more than one year","Insidious onset over many months","Abrupt onset of psychotic symptoms with recovery usually within a few weeks","Absence of any preceding acute stress"]$x$, 2, $x$Acute and transient psychotic disorders have an abrupt onset (within two weeks) of psychotic symptoms, often following acute stress, with full recovery typically within weeks to a few months. Rapidly changing (polymorphic) symptoms are common.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (19, $x$Depressive pseudodementia in the elderly is best distinguished from true dementia by:$x$, $x$["Patients concealing or minimising their memory problems","Gradual insidious progressive decline","Cognitive impairment that improves when the depression is treated","Consistently poor effort with confabulation"]$x$, 2, $x$In depressive pseudodementia the cognitive deficits are secondary to depression and typically reverse once the mood disorder is adequately treated. Such patients often complain prominently of memory loss and answer "I don't know", unlike true dementia.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (20, $x$The hallmark clinical feature of delirium in an elderly patient is:$x$, $x$["Acute onset of fluctuating consciousness and impaired attention","Clear consciousness with stable attention","Slowly progressive memory loss over years","Fixed persecutory delusions with intact orientation"]$x$, 0, $x$Delirium is an acute, fluctuating disturbance of consciousness and attention, usually with disorientation and altered sleep-wake cycle, developing over hours to days. It is a medical emergency requiring identification of the underlying cause.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (21, $x$Which feature most reliably differentiates delirium from dementia?$x$, $x$["Acute onset with clouding of consciousness","Presence of memory impairment","Occurrence in elderly patients","Presence of disorientation"]$x$, 0, $x$Both delirium and dementia impair memory and orientation, but delirium is distinguished by acute onset, clouding and fluctuation of consciousness, and impaired attention. Dementia typically has a gradual onset with clear consciousness until late stages.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (22, $x$According to standard suicide risk assessment, which factor increases the risk of completed suicide?$x$, $x$["Strong social and family support","Female sex and younger age","Male sex, living alone, and a previous suicide attempt","Absence of any psychiatric illness"]$x$, 2, $x$Higher risk of completed suicide is associated with male sex, older age, social isolation, previous attempts, chronic illness and psychiatric disorder, as captured by tools like the SAD PERSONS scale. A prior attempt is one of the strongest predictors.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (23, $x$A patient who has a definite suicidal plan, the means available, and has settled personal affairs is best classified as being at:$x$, $x$["Risk only of self-harm, not suicide","Low risk","High (imminent) risk requiring urgent intervention","No current risk"]$x$, 2, $x$The presence of a specific plan, available lethal means, and preparatory acts such as making a will or giving away belongings indicates high, imminent suicide risk. Such a patient needs constant observation and emergency psychiatric intervention.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (24, $x$Deliberate self-harm differs from suicide primarily in that:$x$, $x$["It never causes physical injury","The primary intention is usually not to die","It carries no risk of future suicide","It is always a sign of psychosis"]$x$, 1, $x$In deliberate self-harm the intent is usually to relieve distress or communicate rather than to end life, though injury does occur. However, self-harm is an important risk factor for later completed suicide and must be taken seriously.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (25, $x$The shift from long-stay mental hospitals to community-based care is known as:$x$, $x$["Milieu therapy","Institutionalisation","Custodial care","Deinstitutionalisation"]$x$, 3, $x$Deinstitutionalisation is the policy of moving patients from large psychiatric institutions to community-based services and rehabilitation. It aims to reduce chronic institutional dependence and promote social reintegration.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (26, $x$The main aim of psychiatric (psychosocial) rehabilitation is to:$x$, $x$["Help the person attain optimal functioning and social reintegration","Provide lifelong custodial hospital care","Achieve complete cure of the underlying illness","Replace all pharmacological treatment"]$x$, 0, $x$Psychosocial rehabilitation focuses on restoring the individual's skills, functioning and social roles despite residual illness, promoting independence and community living. It includes vocational training, social-skills training and family support.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (27, $x$Which of the following is considered a psychiatric emergency?$x$, $x$["A patient expressing active suicidal intent with a plan","A patient requesting a routine follow-up appointment","A stable long-term medication review","Mild situational anxiety before an examination"]$x$, 0, $x$A psychiatric emergency is an acute disturbance of behaviour, thought or mood that, if untreated, may harm the patient or others; active suicidal intent with a plan is a clear example. Immediate assessment and safety measures are required.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (28, $x$The immediate priority in managing an acutely violent, agitated psychiatric patient is:$x$, $x$["Arranging occupational therapy","Ensuring the safety of the patient, staff and others","Starting long-term mood-stabiliser therapy","Obtaining a detailed past psychiatric history"]$x$, 1, $x$In a psychiatric emergency involving aggression, the first priority is ensuring safety through de-escalation, adequate staffing and, if needed, physical restraint and rapid tranquillisation. History and definitive treatment follow once the situation is controlled.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (29, $x$A half-way home in psychiatric rehabilitation is best described as:$x$, $x$["A closed custodial institution for chronic patients","A transitional residential facility bridging hospital and independent community living","An acute-care inpatient psychiatric ward","A centre providing only outpatient medication"]$x$, 1, $x$A half-way home is a supervised transitional residence for recovering psychiatric patients who no longer need hospital care but are not yet ready for fully independent living. It helps them relearn social and daily-living skills before community reintegration.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$)
) as v(pos, question, options, ci, exp, topic, diff);

-- 37-obg-paediatrics.txt — 30 questions
with b as (
  insert into tests (title, topic, difficulty, duration_minutes)
  values ($x$w3-obg-d — ingested draft, verify before trusting$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, 'medium', 60)
  returning id
)
insert into questions (test_id, position, question, options, correct_index, explanation, topic, difficulty)
select b.id, v.pos::int, v.question, v.options::jsonb, v.ci::int, v.exp, v.topic, v.diff
from b, (values
  (0, $x$The most common congenital heart disease in children is:$x$, $x$["Tetralogy of Fallot","Patent ductus arteriosus","Ventricular septal defect","Atrial septal defect"]$x$, 2, $x$Ventricular septal defect is the single most common congenital heart defect, accounting for roughly a quarter to a third of all cases seen in children.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (1, $x$Which of the following is a cyanotic congenital heart disease?$x$, $x$["Patent ductus arteriosus","Tetralogy of Fallot","Ventricular septal defect","Atrial septal defect"]$x$, 1, $x$Tetralogy of Fallot causes right-to-left shunting and is a classic cyanotic lesion, whereas ASD, VSD and PDA are acyanotic left-to-right shunts.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (2, $x$A continuous "machinery" murmur best heard below the left clavicle is characteristic of:$x$, $x$["Atrial septal defect","Coarctation of the aorta","Patent ductus arteriosus","Ventricular septal defect"]$x$, 2, $x$A patent ductus arteriosus produces a continuous machinery murmur in the left infraclavicular area because abnormal flow persists through both systole and diastole.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (3, $x$Upper-limb hypertension with weak, delayed femoral pulses (radio-femoral delay) suggests:$x$, $x$["Ventricular septal defect","Coarctation of the aorta","Patent ductus arteriosus","Transposition of the great arteries"]$x$, 1, $x$Coarctation narrows the aorta, producing upper-limb hypertension with weak, delayed femoral pulses and a measurable pressure gradient between the arms and the legs.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (4, $x$A wide, fixed splitting of the second heart sound is the classic auscultatory finding in:$x$, $x$["Atrial septal defect","Ventricular septal defect","Pulmonary stenosis","Patent ductus arteriosus"]$x$, 0, $x$The wide, fixed splitting of the second heart sound reflects the constant left-to-right shunt across an atrial septal defect, which does not vary with respiration.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (5, $x$Tetralogy of Fallot consists of a ventricular septal defect, overriding aorta, pulmonary stenosis and:$x$, $x$["Patent ductus arteriosus","Right ventricular hypertrophy","Left ventricular hypertrophy","Atrial septal defect"]$x$, 1, $x$The tetralogy comprises a ventricular septal defect, overriding aorta, pulmonary stenosis and right ventricular hypertrophy that develops from the outflow obstruction.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (6, $x$The commonest cyanotic congenital heart disease presenting in the first days of life is:$x$, $x$["Total anomalous pulmonary venous connection","Tetralogy of Fallot","Tricuspid atresia","Transposition of the great arteries"]$x$, 3, $x$Transposition of the great arteries is the commonest cyanotic lesion presenting in the first days of life; survival depends on mixing through a PDA or a septal defect.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (7, $x$During a hypercyanotic ("tet") spell, squatting relieves cyanosis mainly by:$x$, $x$["Lowering pulmonary vascular resistance","Decreasing systemic venous return","Slowing the heart rate","Increasing systemic vascular resistance and reducing the right-to-left shunt"]$x$, 3, $x$Squatting kinks the femoral arteries and raises systemic vascular resistance, which reduces right-to-left shunting and forces more blood through the lungs, easing cyanosis.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (8, $x$The commonest cause of acute bronchiolitis in infants is:$x$, $x$["Haemophilus influenzae","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Parainfluenza virus","Respiratory syncytial virus"]$x$, 3, $x$Respiratory syncytial virus is responsible for the majority of cases of acute bronchiolitis in infants under two years of age, particularly during winter epidemics.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (9, $x$A barking cough with inspiratory stridor and a "steeple sign" on neck X-ray in a toddler indicates:$x$, $x$["Acute epiglottitis","Laryngotracheobronchitis (croup)","Bronchiolitis","Foreign body aspiration"]$x$, 1, $x$Croup is a viral (usually parainfluenza) infection producing a barking cough, inspiratory stridor and subglottic narrowing seen as the steeple sign on a neck radiograph.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (10, $x$An aspirated foreign body in a child most commonly lodges in the:$x$, $x$["Right main bronchus","Trachea","Left main bronchus","Larynx"]$x$, 0, $x$An aspirated foreign body most often enters the right main bronchus because it is wider, shorter and more vertical than the left, making it the path of least resistance.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (11, $x$An episode of childhood diarrhoea is labelled "persistent" when it lasts:$x$, $x$["More than 30 days","14 days or more","More than 3 days","More than 7 days"]$x$, 1, $x$By standard paediatric and WHO definition, an episode of diarrhoea lasting 14 days or longer is termed persistent diarrhoea, distinguishing it from shorter acute diarrhoea.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (12, $x$Diarrhoea with visible blood in the stools (dysentery) in a child is most commonly caused by:$x$, $x$["Rotavirus","Giardia lamblia","Vibrio cholerae","Shigella"]$x$, 3, $x$Dysentery means diarrhoea with visible blood, and Shigella is the commonest cause of bacillary dysentery in children; rotavirus and cholera produce watery, non-bloody stools.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (13, $x$Coeliac disease in children is caused by an immune reaction to:$x$, $x$["Fructose","Lactose","Gluten (gliadin)","Cow's milk protein"]$x$, 2, $x$Coeliac disease is an immune-mediated enteropathy triggered by the gliadin fraction of gluten, causing villous atrophy; anti-tissue transglutaminase antibodies aid diagnosis.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (14, $x$"Red-currant-jelly" stools with a palpable sausage-shaped abdominal mass in an infant suggest:$x$, $x$["Necrotizing enterocolitis","Pyloric stenosis","Intussusception","Hirschsprung disease"]$x$, 2, $x$Intussusception, the telescoping of one bowel segment into another, classically produces red-currant-jelly stools, colicky pain and a palpable sausage-shaped mass in infants.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (15, $x$Hirschsprung disease is characterized by:$x$, $x$["Absence of ganglion cells in the distal bowel","Hypertrophy of the pyloric muscle","Telescoping of one bowel segment into another","Villous atrophy of the small intestine"]$x$, 0, $x$Hirschsprung disease results from failed migration of neural crest cells, leaving the distal bowel aganglionic; it presents with delayed passage of meconium and constipation.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (16, $x$The most common organism causing urinary tract infection in children is:$x$, $x$["Proteus mirabilis","Klebsiella pneumoniae","Escherichia coli","Staphylococcus aureus"]$x$, 2, $x$Escherichia coli is by far the commonest organism causing urinary tract infection in children, responsible for the great majority of both cystitis and pyelonephritis cases.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (17, $x$Acute post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis in a child typically follows infection with:$x$, $x$["Staphylococcus aureus","Group A beta-haemolytic streptococcus","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Escherichia coli"]$x$, 1, $x$Acute post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis follows throat or skin infection with nephritogenic group A streptococcus, presenting with haematuria, oedema, hypertension and low C3.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (18, $x$The most common primary malignant renal tumour of childhood is:$x$, $x$["Transitional cell carcinoma","Neuroblastoma","Wilms tumour (nephroblastoma)","Renal cell carcinoma"]$x$, 2, $x$Wilms tumour (nephroblastoma) is the commonest primary renal malignancy of childhood, typically presenting as a painless, unilateral abdominal mass in a young child.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (19, $x$The most common clinical type of cerebral palsy is:$x$, $x$["Spastic","Dyskinetic (athetoid)","Ataxic","Hypotonic"]$x$, 0, $x$Spastic cerebral palsy is the most common clinical type, characterized by increased muscle tone, brisk deep tendon reflexes and velocity-dependent resistance to passive movement.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (20, $x$In children older than 5 years, the two commonest causes of acute bacterial meningitis are:$x$, $x$["Streptococcus pneumoniae and Neisseria meningitidis","Mycobacterium tuberculosis and Cryptococcus","Group B streptococcus and Escherichia coli","Listeria monocytogenes and Staphylococcus aureus"]$x$, 0, $x$Beyond the neonatal period and infancy, Streptococcus pneumoniae and Neisseria meningitidis are the leading causes of acute pyogenic meningitis in older children.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (21, $x$Simple cyanotic breath-holding spells in a toddler are:$x$, $x$["A form of epilepsy needing anticonvulsants","An indication for lifelong cardiac pacing","Benign spells triggered by crying or anger that resolve with age","Caused by underlying structural brain disease"]$x$, 2, $x$Cyanotic breath-holding spells are benign, provoked by crying, anger or frustration, and typically resolve spontaneously by school age without requiring anticonvulsant therapy.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (22, $x$Beta-thalassaemia major is characterized by:$x$, $x$["Deficiency of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase","A structural point mutation producing HbS","Antibody-mediated red cell destruction","Deficient synthesis of beta-globin chains with raised HbF"]$x$, 3, $x$Beta-thalassaemia major arises from reduced or absent beta-globin chain synthesis, causing severe transfusion-dependent anaemia with a compensatory rise in fetal haemoglobin.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (23, $x$Haemophilia A in children is due to deficiency of:$x$, $x$["Factor VII, autosomal recessive","Von Willebrand factor, autosomal dominant","Factor IX, inherited X-linked recessive","Factor VIII, inherited X-linked recessive"]$x$, 3, $x$Haemophilia A is an X-linked recessive disorder caused by deficiency of clotting factor VIII, presenting in boys with haemarthroses and deep soft-tissue bleeds.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (24, $x$The most common malignancy of childhood is:$x$, $x$["Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia","Retinoblastoma","Osteosarcoma","Wilms tumour"]$x$, 0, $x$Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia is the commonest malignancy of childhood, peaking between 2 and 5 years and presenting with pallor, fever, bleeding and bone pain.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (25, $x$Type 1 diabetes mellitus in children is caused by:$x$, $x$["Excess growth hormone secretion","Peripheral insulin resistance","A defect in the insulin receptor gene","Autoimmune destruction of pancreatic beta cells"]$x$, 3, $x$Type 1 diabetes results from T-cell-mediated autoimmune destruction of pancreatic islet beta cells, leading to absolute insulin deficiency and lifelong insulin dependence.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (26, $x$A type 1 diabetic child with vomiting, deep sighing (Kussmaul) breathing and a fruity breath odour most likely has:$x$, $x$["Hypoglycaemia","Hyperosmolar non-ketotic coma","Lactic acidosis","Diabetic ketoacidosis"]$x$, 3, $x$Vomiting, deep sighing Kussmaul breathing and a fruity acetone breath odour indicate diabetic ketoacidosis, caused by insulin deficiency with ketone accumulation and metabolic acidosis.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (27, $x$Long-standing large left-to-right shunts (e.g., VSD) may lead to Eisenmenger syndrome, which is:$x$, $x$["Rheumatic valve stenosis","Spontaneous closure of the defect","Reversal of the shunt to right-to-left with cyanosis","Development of infective endocarditis"]$x$, 2, $x$Persistent large left-to-right shunts raise pulmonary vascular resistance until the shunt reverses to right-to-left (Eisenmenger syndrome), producing cyanosis and precluding surgical repair.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (28, $x$Coarctation of the aorta is classically associated with which chromosomal disorder?$x$, $x$["Down syndrome","Edward syndrome","Klinefelter syndrome","Turner syndrome"]$x$, 3, $x$Coarctation of the aorta is classically associated with Turner syndrome (45,X) and with a bicuspid aortic valve, so femoral pulses should always be checked in such girls.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (29, $x$The chief complication requiring iron-chelation therapy in transfusion-dependent beta-thalassaemia is:$x$, $x$["Iron overload (haemosiderosis)","Folate deficiency","Vitamin B12 deficiency","Hypercalcaemia"]$x$, 0, $x$Repeated transfusions in beta-thalassaemia major cause iron overload (haemosiderosis) affecting the heart, liver and endocrine glands, necessitating iron-chelation therapy such as desferrioxamine.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$hard$x$)
) as v(pos, question, options, ci, exp, topic, diff);

-- 38-gap-close.txt — 23 questions
with b as (
  insert into tests (title, topic, difficulty, duration_minutes)
  values ($x$38-gap-close — ingested draft, verify before trusting$x$, $x$Mixed$x$, 'medium', 60)
  returning id
)
insert into questions (test_id, position, question, options, correct_index, explanation, topic, difficulty)
select b.id, v.pos::int, v.question, v.options::jsonb, v.ci::int, v.exp, v.topic, v.diff
from b, (values
  (0, $x$The Widal test is a serological test used in the diagnosis of$x$, $x$["Dengue","Tuberculosis","Malaria","Enteric fever, or typhoid"]$x$, 3, $x$The Widal test detects antibodies against the O and H antigens of Salmonella typhi and paratyphi in the patient's serum. A rising titre in paired samples supports a diagnosis of enteric fever, though it has limited specificity.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (1, $x$The tuberculin, or Mantoux, test is an example of which type of hypersensitivity reaction?$x$, $x$["Type III, immune complex","Type II, cytotoxic","Type I, immediate","Type IV, delayed cell-mediated"]$x$, 3, $x$The Mantoux reaction is a Type IV delayed hypersensitivity response mediated by sensitised T-lymphocytes, read at 48 to 72 hours by measuring the diameter of induration. It indicates prior exposure or infection, not necessarily active disease.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (2, $x$The ELISA test is most widely used as a screening test for$x$, $x$["Diabetes mellitus","Hypertension","HIV infection","Iron deficiency"]$x$, 2, $x$The enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay detects antibodies or antigens using an enzyme-linked colour change and is the standard screening test for HIV. A reactive ELISA is confirmed by a more specific test such as Western blot before diagnosis.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (3, $x$In the human malarial parasite, the asexual cycle that causes the clinical fever paroxysms takes place in the$x$, $x$["Salivary glands of the mosquito","Liver cells only","White blood cells","Red blood cells"]$x$, 3, $x$After an initial silent liver (exo-erythrocytic) stage, Plasmodium multiplies asexually inside red blood cells, and their synchronous rupture releases merozoites and pyrogens that cause the periodic fever paroxysms. The sexual cycle occurs in the mosquito.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (4, $x$Which immunoglobulin is the first antibody produced in a primary immune response and is the largest in size?$x$, $x$["IgA","IgE","IgG","IgM"]$x$, 3, $x$IgM is a pentamer, the largest antibody, and is the first immunoglobulin produced early in a primary infection, making it a marker of recent or acute infection. IgG appears later and predominates in the secondary response.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (5, $x$On which culture medium does Escherichia coli, a lactose fermenter, produce pink colonies?$x$, $x$["MacConkey agar","Chocolate agar","Nutrient agar","Lowenstein-Jensen medium"]$x$, 0, $x$MacConkey agar is a selective and differential medium on which lactose-fermenting organisms such as E. coli form pink colonies, while non-lactose fermenters remain pale. Lowenstein-Jensen medium is used instead for growing Mycobacterium tuberculosis.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (6, $x$The oral polio vaccine developed by Albert Sabin is an example of which type of vaccine?$x$, $x$["Live attenuated vaccine","Killed or inactivated vaccine","Toxoid vaccine","Conjugate vaccine"]$x$, 0, $x$The Sabin oral polio vaccine contains live attenuated virus that replicates in the gut and produces both local and systemic immunity. The Salk injectable polio vaccine, in contrast, is a killed or inactivated preparation.$x$, $x$Basic Sciences$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (7, $x$According to Freud, the part of the personality that operates on the reality principle and mediates between instinctual drives and social demands is the$x$, $x$["Id","Ego","Libido","Superego"]$x$, 1, $x$Freud described the ego as operating on the reality principle, balancing the demands of the pleasure-seeking id against the moral standards of the superego. It uses defence mechanisms to manage conflict and anxiety.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (8, $x$According to Erik Erikson, the central psychosocial task of infancy, in the first year of life, is$x$, $x$["Initiative versus guilt","Trust versus mistrust","Identity versus role confusion","Autonomy versus shame and doubt"]$x$, 1, $x$Erikson's first psychosocial stage, in the first year, is trust versus mistrust, in which consistent, responsive caregiving fosters a basic sense of trust. Identity versus role confusion is the task of adolescence.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (9, $x$The behaviour-therapy technique in which a patient earns tokens for desirable behaviour that can later be exchanged for privileges is called$x$, $x$["Token economy","Systematic desensitisation","Flooding","Aversion therapy"]$x$, 0, $x$A token economy applies operant conditioning by reinforcing desired behaviour with tokens that are exchangeable for rewards, and is used in chronic psychiatric and rehabilitation settings. It shapes behaviour through positive reinforcement.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (10, $x$Which is an example of a therapeutic communication technique?$x$, $x$["Giving false reassurance","Changing the subject when a topic is difficult","Offering personal opinions and advice","Asking open-ended questions to encourage the patient to talk"]$x$, 3, $x$Open-ended questions invite the patient to express thoughts and feelings in their own words and are a core therapeutic communication technique. False reassurance, giving advice and changing the subject are non-therapeutic blocks to communication.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$easy$x$),
  (11, $x$A nurse who responds to a frightened patient by saying everything will definitely be fine is using which non-therapeutic communication block?$x$, $x$["Clarification","Focusing","Reflection","False reassurance"]$x$, 3, $x$Telling a patient that everything will be fine is false reassurance, which dismisses genuine feelings and can block further disclosure. Therapeutic alternatives include acknowledging the fear and exploring the patient's concerns.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (12, $x$Crisis intervention is best described as a form of therapy that is$x$, $x$["Long-term and focused on childhood conflicts","Aimed at restructuring the entire personality","Delivered only in an inpatient psychiatric unit","Short-term and focused on the immediate problem and restoring function"]$x$, 3, $x$Crisis intervention is a brief, focused, reality-oriented therapy that helps the person cope with an immediate stressful situation and return to their previous level of functioning. A crisis is usually self-limiting and resolves within about six weeks.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (13, $x$In group therapy, the sense of hope a member gains from seeing others who have coped successfully is a curative factor known as$x$, $x$["Instillation of hope","Catharsis","Universality","Altruism"]$x$, 0, $x$Instillation of hope, described by Irvin Yalom, is the encouragement members draw from observing others who have improved, and it sustains engagement in therapy. Universality is the relief of learning that one's problems are shared by others.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (14, $x$The defence mechanism in which unacceptable feelings are channelled into socially acceptable and often constructive activity is$x$, $x$["Sublimation","Regression","Denial","Projection"]$x$, 0, $x$Sublimation redirects unacceptable impulses into socially valued activities, such as channelling aggression into competitive sport. It is regarded as one of the more mature and adaptive defence mechanisms.$x$, $x$Mental Health Nursing$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (15, $x$An Rh-negative woman is most likely to become sensitised to the Rh antigen$x$, $x$["At the time of delivery of an Rh-positive baby or a sensitising event","Only during breastfeeding","During her first pregnancy before any delivery","Only if she receives Rh-negative blood"]$x$, 0, $x$Sensitisation usually occurs when fetal Rh-positive red cells enter the maternal circulation at delivery, miscarriage, or other sensitising events, prompting maternal anti-D antibody formation. The first pregnancy is therefore usually unaffected, while later Rh-positive pregnancies are at risk.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (16, $x$In a pregnant woman with pre-existing diabetes, the preferred agent for glycaemic control is$x$, $x$["Insulin","Metformin as the sole agent in all cases","Sulphonylureas","No treatment until after delivery"]$x$, 0, $x$Insulin is the preferred treatment for diabetes in pregnancy because it does not cross the placenta and allows tight, titratable glycaemic control. Good control reduces the risk of macrosomia, congenital anomaly and neonatal hypoglycaemia.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (17, $x$Intrauterine growth restriction is best defined as a fetus whose estimated weight falls below which percentile for gestational age?$x$, $x$["25th percentile","10th percentile","90th percentile","50th percentile"]$x$, 1, $x$Intrauterine growth restriction refers to a fetus that fails to reach its growth potential, conventionally an estimated fetal weight below the 10th percentile for gestational age. It is monitored with serial ultrasound and Doppler studies of fetal blood flow.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (18, $x$A drug commonly used as a tocolytic to suppress preterm uterine contractions is$x$, $x$["Nifedipine","Misoprostol","Ergometrine","Oxytocin"]$x$, 0, $x$Nifedipine, a calcium channel blocker, is widely used as a tocolytic to relax the uterus and delay preterm labour, allowing time for corticosteroids to mature the fetal lungs. Oxytocin, ergometrine and misoprostol instead stimulate uterine contraction.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (19, $x$Antenatal corticosteroids are given to a woman in threatened preterm labour primarily to$x$, $x$["Stop the uterine contractions","Treat maternal infection","Accelerate fetal lung maturity and surfactant production","Raise the maternal blood pressure"]$x$, 2, $x$Antenatal corticosteroids such as betamethasone or dexamethasone accelerate fetal lung maturation and surfactant production, reducing respiratory distress syndrome, intraventricular haemorrhage and neonatal death. They are given between 24 and 34 weeks when preterm birth is likely.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (20, $x$Premature rupture of the membranes carries the greatest risk of which complication to the mother and fetus?$x$, $x$["Ascending intrauterine infection, or chorioamnionitis","Macrosomia","Gestational diabetes","Postmaturity"]$x$, 0, $x$Once the membranes rupture, the protective barrier is lost and organisms can ascend from the vagina, so chorioamnionitis is the principal danger, along with cord prolapse and preterm birth. Management balances the risk of infection against that of prematurity.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$medium$x$),
  (21, $x$Magnesium sulphate given to a woman in preterm labour before 32 weeks also provides which benefit to the baby?$x$, $x$["Prevention of congenital heart disease","Stimulation of fetal breathing","Neuroprotection, reducing the risk of cerebral palsy","Prevention of neonatal jaundice"]$x$, 2, $x$Magnesium sulphate given to women at risk of very preterm birth has a fetal neuroprotective effect, reducing the incidence and severity of cerebral palsy. This is a separate indication from its use in controlling eclamptic seizures.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$hard$x$),
  (22, $x$A woman with heart disease is at greatest haemodynamic risk during pregnancy at which time?$x$, $x$["Only during the second trimester","The first trimester only","Only before conception","Around 28 to 32 weeks, in labour, and immediately postpartum"]$x$, 3, $x$Cardiac output peaks around 28 to 32 weeks and again during labour and the immediate postpartum period as blood returns to the circulation, so these are the times of greatest risk of cardiac decompensation. Care focuses on limiting exertion and careful fluid balance.$x$, $x$Obstetrics & Child Health$x$, $x$hard$x$)
